report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 30 year old male with fever and seizures and no other past medical history.

MEDICATIONS: Versed,  Ativan, Phosphenytoin


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Patient is intubated and is being evaluated for status epilepticus.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This acute emergency room record demonstrates a markedly abnormal but dynamic pattern. As the tracing begins, the overall background is slow, even slightly discontinuous. There is an area in the right hemisphere of irregular epileptiform activity with sharp waves or spikes maximum at T6 P4 02 but with variability. There is even a spike that starts posteriorly and then demonstrates spread to T4 T6. Some of the discharges are followed by right frontally predominant rhythmic delta. As the recording continues, there is less
in the background suppression following the spikes,  the epileptiform activity is present but does
not build up into bursts and the overall background is more continuous. In addition, at the end of the record, it is returned mixed frequency activity.

HR:	N/A


IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1.	A complex, polyphasic epileptiform discharge in the right posterior quadrant with variable maximum.
2. 	Right frontotemporal delta.
3. 	Background slowing.
4. 	Intermittently discontinuous record.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports an irritative process. In addition, there is focal slowing and bilateral background slowing. Correlation with clinical history is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old woman with epilepsy, history of stroke, right-sided weakness, and headache 3 times per week.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Hydralazine, Labetalol, Lasix

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrodes placement with 1 channel of EKG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized, but demonstrates rhythmic background slowing with a 7.5 Hz alpha rhythm. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. The background slowing may be correlated with this patient's clinical history and medication.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old left handed gentleman with epilepsy, hepatitis C, recurrent hepatic encephalopathy, now with recurrent confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lasix, Vancomycin
INTRODUCTION: Digital EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is poorly responsive, wearing a hard collar and intubated.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes generous alpha frequency activity of 11 Hz identified in the occipital temporal regions bilaterally and more significant rhythmic theta and some delta in the frontocentral and parietal regions.
HR: 80 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No spike in wave activity was seen today. The background slowing may be due to this patient's underlying hepatic encephalopathy. Of note, this patient was previously treated with Topamax and Lamictal, which are not listed as his medications today.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 42 year old male with paranoid schizophrenia, auditory and
visual hallucinations, and a single blackout spell with shaking.

MEDICATIONS: Folate, Singulair, Risperdal, Celexa, Benztropine·

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens the patient seems quite
nervous with frequent eye blink. The alpha rhythm does achieve 8.5 Hz.
Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing an increase in slowing of the
background. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. This record does contain somewhat
more 7-8Hz activity than would be normally anticipated In an adult of this age.

HR: 80 bpm

IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Scant excess theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a mild disturbance of cerebral function.
It is just outside the limits of normal for an adult of this age. No epileptiform activity was seen in this EEG or in the previous study.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 44 year old right handed male with a traumatic brain injury December
2008, subsequently developing epilepsy, last seizure 2 weeks ago. Bilateral frontal skull
defects.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are
performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. There is a scant amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Stage II sleep includes
some slightly irregular vertex and spindle activity, congruent with the patient's previous
craniotomy. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. Following photic stimulation as the patient becomes drowsy there is a prominent increase in beta.
Hyperventilation accentuates some of the frontal theta.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild excess frontal theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The craniotomy findings such as the breech rhythm are normal
finding after craniotomy. There is a small amount of excess theta. Overall, this EEG is
improved compared to a previous study dated 6/24/2009. Neither study demonstrated
epileptiform activity. In this individual with continued seizures, a more prolonged study
capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful to characterize epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old woman with a long history of epilepsy, psychosis admitted with recurrent seizures and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Topamax.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is slow and disorganized. In addition, superimposed upon this are bursts of arrhythmic and rhythmic theta and delta, maximum in the right temporal regions but sometimes seen in isolation on the left. The later sections of the recording including drowsiness include frontally-predominant 3-4 Hz high amplitude activity with a suspicious underlying right frontal sharp wave. This is also noted during photic stimulation.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing and disorganization.
2. Rhythmic right temporal epileptiform activity.
3. Right frontal rhythmic high amplitude 3-4 Hz activity as well as perhaps and underlying spike and slow wave complex.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing has been seen intermittently for this individual. The epileptiform activity has also been previously noted. No seizures were recorded, but a search to determine whether or not this patient is postictal or is having an acute metabolic encephalopathy is suggested. ╖

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54-year-old male with epilepsy, hepatic encephalopathy, now in
coma.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Rifaximin, Pentoxifylline, Octreotide, Midodrine

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intubated. There is a fair amount of muscle artifact noted in the background.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly low voltage. There is muscle, underlying slow, rhythmic delta 1.5 Hz and both muscle artifact and beta. The overall frequency is beta. Stimulation of the patient does not activate the record.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Replacement of normal background with a low voltage, beta pattern.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform seizures were identified. This is a markedly abnormal pattern. Considerations for diffuse disturbance of cerebral function as well as exposure to a medication which would produce beta activity should be considered. In comparison to previous studies during this individuals hepatic encephalopathy, this pattern demonstrates worsening of the background slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 55 year old right handed male bus driver with a syncopal spell and many cardiac problems. Obstructive sleep apnea.

MEDICATIONS: Singulair, Diovan, Synthroid, Crestor.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and an asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11-Hz alpha rhythm, which is higher amplitude on the left than the right. In drowsiness and hyperventilation there is a very small amount of shifting temporal theta. Other features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits a subtle driving response.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. A small amount of shifting temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The theta described above can be seen in the context of cerebrovascular disease. The amplitude asymmetry can be seen in normals and is not clinically significant.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 53 year old male status post gunshot wound in 2008 with post traumatic epilepsy and post traumatic syncope occurring 1-7 times per day.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation is attempted. The patient's communication skills are limited.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified bilaterally. There is eye movement and a suggestion of perhaps a skull deformity in the frontal regions bilaterally. A breech rhythm was not noted or a cranial defect was not noted by the tech, however. A small amount of rhythmic frontal theta is noted in the transition to drowsiness, followed by rhythmic vertex waves and then spontaneous arousals. Vertex waves are observed in stage 1 sleep, followed by spontaneous arousals. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting into stage 1 sleep with POSTS, but there is a scant driving response observed.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. A small amount of rhythmic, frontal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are nonspecific and may be correlated with imaging. No epileptiform features were observed. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep may be beneficial.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 72 year old gentleman with multiple severe medical problems, refractory
epilepsy. The patient believes that he is seizure free, but the family notes declining cognition.

MEDICATIONS: Unknown

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were
completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.8 Hz alpha rhythm. There is
prominent, shifting arrhythmic delta activity in the temporal regions. During hyperventilation, there is a brief run of right temporal sharp waves. This is followed by some bitemporal sharp activity. The overall background demonstrates generate.s beta. Primarily in wakefulness there is occasional left temporal delta, but stage 2 sleep is relatively synchronous with symmetric vertex waves, spindles, and K-complexes. Photic stimulation is performed with the patient initially asleep with some shifting asymmetries, but when awake there is a driving response and then another burst of right temporal sharp waves.

HR: 72 bpm and irregular

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Bursts of right temporal sharp waves.
2. Excess theta.
3. Occasional left temporal focal delta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The patient's previous EEG's were not available to date for
comparison. No subclinical or clinical seizures were recorded. Some of the background
slowing, disorganization, and isolated left temporal focal slowing may be part of this patient's underlying ischemic cerebrovascular disease and polycythemia vera.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 27 year old woman pregnant with hyperglycemia coma.
MEDICATIONS: Azithromycin, Ceftriaxone, Insulin, Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is described increasingly responsive during this overnight recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background starts out at a markedly abnormal background with a mixture of theta and delta. The pattern includes some frontally predominant triphasic waves which improve over time and bilateral generalized periodic epileptiform discharges. Focal sharp waves are seen in the left posterior temporal region at T3 and T5, but those are improving to some extent during the course of the record. Over the course of the record there is an increase in spontaneous arousals which are associated with muscle artifact. The discontinuity improves and the triphasics resolve, but the overall starts out with a markedly slow delta/theta pattern and transitions to a very slow, but with increasing theta quantity pattern.
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
2. Triphasic waves.
3. Bilateral frontal generalized periodic complexes.
4. Focal epileptiform activity primarily in the left posterior regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no definitive seizures with characteristic frequency evolution, although there are portions of the record where the frontal sharp waves do appear in trains. Overall, this EEG demonstrates an improving but markedly abnormal process. Ongoing vigilance is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 77 year old male with status post surgery for abdominal aortic aneurysm, now unresponsive. The time and date of his code are unknown.

MEDICATIONS: Vasopressin, EPI, Amidone, Zocor, Protonix, Ceftriaxone, Versed, Morphine

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Patient is intubated but not sedated.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a low voltage, continuous EEG. There is prominent background artifact from one of his bedside devices. In this relatively low voltage, somewhat suppressed background there is more delta, theta and even some alpha frequency activity in the frontal regions. Tactile stimulation produces some increase in theta.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A pattern of mostly delta and theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are nonspecific and can be seen in the diffuse disturbance of many different causes. No epileptiform features were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old left handed male with hepatic failure.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Zofran, Valganciclovir, Andromeda, Insulin Protonix, Septra Bactrim, Mycamine, Daptomycin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background includes a rhythmic theta pattern. Brief pairs or isolated bursts of frontally predominant 3.5 to 4.5 Hz spike and wave activity are noted.

HR: 114 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic slowing.
2. Frontally predominant 3 to 5 Hz spike and wave activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing is a nonspecific finding and can be see in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function due to many different causes. This EEG is not as slow or suppressed as the study on 01/25/2010. The epileptiform activity suggests a generalized mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old left handed make with long standing epilepsy, status post
recent liver transplant, now with recurrent seizures over the weekend, dramatic MRI changes, and obtundation.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Cipro, Lovenox, Daptomycin, Valganciclovir, Insulin, Prednisone

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is trached and poorly responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes a mixed frequency pattern
with generous delta and smaller amounts of theta. The most notable features about this record include focal slowing in the right hemisphere with arrhythmic delta and nearly continuous, somewhat periodic sharp waves in the right hemisphere with variable maximum and a generous field of spread. Using an average reference they appear to be maximum at 02, but there is generous involvement at C4, T6, and P4. There is a somewhat unusual dipole and there is variability in the discharges. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in theta.

HR: 90 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Continuous focal slowing from the right hemisphere.
2. Sharp waves from the right with a generous field of spread maximum in the posterior
quadrants.
3. Generalized background slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG differs significantly from last weeks EEG which
demonstrated more of a theta frequency pattern with low voltage frontal, symmetric
spike and wave activity. No seizures were recorded, but this a quite prominent epileptiform focus with a generous field of spread.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old male with spells.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra and Retrovirals.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is awake and drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is generous beta and theta.
HR: 104 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess beta.
2. Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION The pattern of increasing theta has been previously observed for this individual. Again, no epileptiform features are observed. This is his 13th EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 60 year old woman with pontine hemorrhage and locked-in syndrome.

MEDICATIONS: Ciprofloxacin, Hydralazine, Zosyn, Pantoprazole, Metoprolol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is resting in bed. The background EEG is somewhat disorganized and is comprised primarily of rhythmic theta frequency activity with smaller amounts of underlying delta. Much of the theta frequency activity is 7 Hz with smaller quantities of5.5 Hz activity. Intermittent coughing is observed. It is not specifically associated with a change in-the background. There ate occasional bursts of arrhythmic delta activity identified from either hemisphere. Stimulation of the patient does not particularly impact the record. The record is not long enough to record definitive sleep cycles.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Replacement of normal background primarily with a theta frequency pattern.
2. Underlying arrhythmic delta activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. If appropriate, a longer study to identify sleep/wake cycles may be of value. An alternative would be to consider SSEPs.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 53 year old woman with refractory epilepsy since age 30, obstructive sleep apnea, and morbid obesity.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Tegretol,

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This an awake and sleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of background theta. Eye movement artifact is picked up in wakefulness I on the anterior temporal electrodes, but there is also some left temporal irregular slowing and sharp waves. Features of drowsiness include an increase in synchronicity or arrhythmicity of the background. followed by brief vertex waves. Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.

HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing.
2. Left temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: In maximal wakefulness the background EEG is well organized and at the end of the record, maximal wakefulness is-characterized by 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm. In this individual with obstructive sleep apnea, some of the background theta may represent a drowsy pattern. The left temporal focal features, including sharp waves in wakefulness and sleep, have been previously described.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 27 year old woman comes with an episode of profound hypoglycemia, seizure, brain injury, now with a seizure today and associated catatonia.

MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Insulin, Lamictal, Heparin, Levothyroxine, Protonix, Lorazepam, Nitrofurantoin, Benadryl

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient has been uncooperative and was sedated for the study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a continuous pattern primarily with a theta delta frequency pattern and intermittent bursts of frontally predominant rhythmic delta activity. Some of these are more prominent in the right compared to the left. The FIRDA is more prominent as the individual becomes drowsy. She seems to be inattentive, intermittently alerting and looking about. This pattern is followed by some frontal delta. Lambda is observed. The patient is carefully monitored by a nurse and the technologist during the study.
HR: 120 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed today. When the patient is cooperative, it may be important to reassess the background. The patient's current mental state, however, is not ictal although it may be toxic or metabolic or postictal.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 year old female presented with a Brainstem stroke, persistently unresponsive.

MEDICATIONS: ASA, Cipro, Heparin, Simvastatin, Isosorbide, Coreg.,

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Patient is intubated but is stimulated during the record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly slow with a mixture of theta and delta. In addition, there are sharp wave complexes noted in the record including right central parietal and left posterior temporal. Stimulation of the patient produces little in the way of alerting response.

HR: 110 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Markedly slow background.
2. Epileptiform activity in both hemispheres, some of which appears in trains or is somewhat periodic in nature.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a significant disturbance of cerebral function affecting both gray and white matter. The epileptiform activity is of unclear significance but may merit additional intervention and evaluation.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 20 year old male with mental retardation and epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Ativan, Keppra, Trileptal,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is slow, disorganized, and lacking in the normal morphologies of an awake EEG. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record and produces occasional bursts of rhythmic, bifrontal sharp waves. In stage 1 and stage 2 sleep there are rudimentary vertex waves and spindles. In addition, frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave complexes with a slow spike and wave frequency are identified. These are maximum on the left, but have some bilateral representation. Photic stimulation does not clearly activate the record and is performed while the Individual in stage 2 sleep where the epileptiform activity is prominent.

HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Frontal spike and slow wave activity and left frontal spike and stow wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings were seen in 2 previous EEGs dated August 8, 2008 and September 28, 2008.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 84 year old gentleman with dementia, right parietal stroke, aggressive behavior and profound hemiparesis more remarkable than expected for infarct.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Plavix, Aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is quite drowsy throughout the record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a low voltage theta pattern which is slightly slower on the left compared to the right with a bit of right posterior quadrant delta. The focal slowing in the right posterior quadrant becomes a bit more prominent as the patient becomes drowsy. In addition, there is higher amplitude rhythmic theta on the right. The overall background is quite slow. Due to the patient's behavior, hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed. At some point, the patient has his eyes open and appears to be resting quietly, but the background remains quite slow.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
2. Superimposed rhythmic slowing on the right posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function. The prior dementia may augment the slowing identified in this individual.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 29 year old right handed male with refractory epilepsy, Lennox-Gastaut
syndrome, rare, early morning seizures none serious at this time.

MEDICATIONS: Carbatrol, Zonisamide.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is cooperative.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a dynamic pattern. There are brief sections of the record where the EEG is medium amplitude, reasonably well organized with a 6 hertz background. This is disrupted by bursts of rhythmic, frontally predominant delta. In addition, there is arrhythmic delta activity sometimes identified in the occipital scalp region. There are shifting asymmetries but some of the arrhythmic delta activity is higher amplitude on the left compared to the right. Within the bursts of delta, there are subtle, slow, frontal spike and slow wave complexes. The epileptiform activity is not as prominent as the frontal delta. Hyperventilation produces prominent bursts of delta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Markedly abnormal background.
2. Frontal spike and slow wave activity.
3. Occipital delta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to previous studies. No clinical seizures  were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old gentleman with migraine headaches, memory loss, and difficulty concentrating.
MEDICATIONS: Lasix, Insulin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a scant 10 Hz alpha rhythm but there is excess, low voltage 4 Hz beta activity identified. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing with vertex waves in stage I sleep. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background and an increase in some faster frequency activity.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess 4 Hz activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The findings described above are nonspecific and can be seen in memory impairment. Comparison with this patient's history and imaging is important. There was no report of exposure to sedative hypnotic medications which could contribute to the pattern described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 63 year old male with headaches, recurrent syncope, peripheral
neuropathy, lifelong schizophrenia, history of perinatal injury.
MEDICATIONS: Seroquel
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG
demonstrates intermittent slowing and disorganization. There are sections of the record
where the background is more organized with brief, 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm but much of
the time the alpha is slower at 8.3 Hz with some theta frequency activity mixed in.
Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild background slowing.
2. Disorganization for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In this individual with a history of head trauma and
longstanding schizophrenia, the findings are less prominent than expected. There are
no epileptiform features noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old right handed male with childhood epilepsy, currently experiencing seizures described by a funny feeling in his body lasting minutes. He also reports tonic clonic seizures, profound psychiatric impairment.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is a 1-hour EEG. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall background EEG is reasonably well organized with a 10.3 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of shifting slowing. Notable in this record are just prior, during, and after hyperventilation are bursts of high amplitude frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and slow wave complexes. These are high amplitude, frontally predominant, symmetric, and typically occur in bursts lasting 2 seconds, but up to 3 seconds. They are symmetric, bifrontal, with a polyspike component. Features of drowsiness include vertex waves. K-complexes are noted in stage 2 sleep. Dyshormia is noted as the patient transitions into sleep. In the transition to and from sleep there is some isolated high amplitude or more subtle spike and wave complexes also observed.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for a driving response. In addition, just following 11 Hz spike and wave activity and in the intermediate/frequencies, such as 17 Hz, spike and wave activity is observed.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is significantly different from the initial EEG November 4, 2009 which did not identify generalized spike and wave activity. In that study, hyperventilation was not performed. This EEG is much more supportive of a generalized and focal mechanism for epilepsy. It is also different in that there is no generalized background slowing noted today.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 35 year old right handed female with childhood epilepsy, previously seizure-free since 2000 but now with Increasing auras and seizures during this pregnancy. After she reduced her Tegretol dose.

MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Levothyroxine.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient reports that she has not experienced a seizure in 3 days and feels normal on the day in question.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, there is an abnormality in the record with a repetitive spike or sharp wave in the right occipital region. This is seen almost at 3 to 5 Hz in frequency. It averages a little more than 3 Hz with a peak of 70 microvolts in the background. This accompanies primarily alpha and theta frequency background with a suggestion of an alpha rhythm on the left of approximately 7.3 Hz, but there is also some 8.5 Hz activity in the background noted. The occipital spiking Is nearly continuous throughout the record. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. The right occipital 02 spike waxes and wanes. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving on the left and does not seem to impact the right occipital spiking. At the end of photic stimulation, however, the spiking seems to be slowing to below 3 Hz.

HR: 78 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Nearly continuous right occipital spike activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings were discussed with the patient. This EEG supports a highly irritative focus in the right occipital cortex.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 53 year old woman who presented with gastroparesis and then had the development of myoclonus, asterixis and nystagmus followed by encephalopathy. Clostridium difficile.
MEDICATIONS: Neurontin, Cyclosporine, CellCept, Prednisone, Heparin, Vancomycin, Avelox, Reglan, Zosyn
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Her previous EEGs are not available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a rhythmic, slow pattern with a mixture of theta and delta. The primary frequency in the background is 1.2 Hz delta with smaller amounts of 6 Hz theta and over 80% of the record is now delta. Theta frequency activity is seen intermittently and sometimes diffusely or in the frontocentral regions. Stimulation of the patient elicits a withdrawal response but not much change in the EEG.
HR: 132 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Moderate-to-marked background slowing.
2. Frontal delta relatively symmetric.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is significantly slower than the previous EEG. Correlation with imaging is suggested.

disturbance of cerebral function and the ictal pattern Is one seen in a chronic, static
encephalopathy emanating from a pediatric pattern.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is a prolonged study for a patient who appeared to have had a subclinical seizure. She was confused during the EEG and somewhat lethargic.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal. The background from the right hemisphere is slow and disorganized. The left hemisphere includes a high amplitude breech rhythm with a left frontal sharp and slow complex with arrhythmic delta activity.
At 9:15 the patient is relatively inattentive and the technologist wraps the head. At some point essentially continuous spiking is noted in the left frontal region.
A seizure is identified at 9:19 characterized by evolution of epileptiform activity in the left frontal region, which is high amplitude with a generous field of spread. The seizure duration is from 19:13:30 to 19:19:59 suggesting that this is a relatively brief seizure. The technologist transitions from this to additional recording at 09:21. After the first event with impaired responsiveness, high amplitude left frontal spiking is noted with a breech rhythm in the abnormal background. The patient's mental status actually improves somewhat. She moves about, although she is confused. The activity remains quite slow in both hemispheres.
There was another brief build up again at 9:40. Artifacts are picked up at 9:35, but again there is prominent spiking in the background with very prominent epileptiform activity.
A third electrographic seizure occurs at 9:58:57. The patient is relatively somnolent. Stimulation of the patient does not occur during this testing, but the seizure stops by itself and as it does the patient moves about.
By the morning of the 7th, she is more consistently awake, out of bed with more rhythmic theta frequency in the background although the patterns in both hemispheres are slow.

After the seizure was over, the patient looks about.

Unusual, right mid temporal to posterior temporal or central temporal periodic sharp waves which were actually picked up in relaxed wakefulness, but not in deeper stages of sleep.

A handful of bilaterally predominantly, almost a posterior triphasic-like wave.

The posteriorly predominant triphasic wave appearing discharge may represent a pled-like phenomenon or a metabolic phenomenon.  No seizures were recorded. CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old male with previous seizures characterized by eyes rolling back in his head, facial twitching, confusion and incontinence, slurred speech, past history of dementia and right temporal lobe gliosis and epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Famotidine
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow. It is a mixture of delta and theta frequency activity. The activity is somewhat more suppressed on the right compared to the left and the right is lower voltage. The left hemisphere demonstrates well defined T1 spike and slow or sharp and slow wave complexes noted as the recording continues. As the recording continues, the patient is awake with eye opening and occasional movements.
The sharp waves and spikes tend to occur as pairs with a brief train of sharp waves and spikes noted at 11:1329. This is followed by an arousal, but no definitive seizures. As the patient drifts back toward sleep, there is a mixture of theta and delta and less eye movement. Occasional automatisms in chewing are noted, but no seizures are recorded.
HR:    72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Prominent left anterior temporal sharp and slow wave and spike and slow wave complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The background slowing is improving compatible with a postictal state. The focal sharp waves support a focal mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old man with a history of epilepsy, now with prolonged generalized tonic/clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Depakote, Keppra, Phenobarbital.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Status Epilepticus
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video long-term EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.  Continuous spike detection software as well as alarm and nurses' notes were used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 40 microvolts.  There is frontocentral beta seen.  No abnormal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures are performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves/PLEDS at FP1 at 1 to 2 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 70 microvolts seen almost continuously throughout the recording, although by the last 24 hours the frequency had diminished and they were only seen in some spurts with inter bursts of more than 10 seconds.  The morphology at the end of the recording was a lot more blunt and of lower amplitude.
Generalized slow waves.
SEIZURES:  During the recording, the patient would have, at the FP1 electrode, rhythmic discharges that would increase in frequency and decrease in amplitude, and then suddenly stop multiple times per hour for the first 10 hours.  Suddenly they subsided and stopped, and for the rest of the recording none were seen.  During the ones that occurred at the beginning of the recording, no clear clinical correlation was noted.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Seizures from the left prefrontal region which subsided after the first 10 hours, and none were seen for the last 50 hours of recording.
Focal sharp waves/PLEDS seen in the left prefrontal region.
Generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of acute structural dysfunction and irritability arising from the left prefrontal region which has a high correlation with an acute structural lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of seizures arising from the same region for the first 10 hours of the recording and none seen in the next 50 hours.  There is also evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology and is likely due, at least in part, to medication effect.  These changes were noted to the primary team during the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  34 year old woman with liver failure, long history of multiple body jolts with drop and loss of consciousness over the past 3-4 years. In this individual with a history of myoclonus and/or tonic clonic seizures, a follow EEG, perhaps in 1 hour with sleep, may be helpful to more fully evaluate this patient.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   61 year old woman who presented cardiac arrest with code in progress outside hospital and was brought in for further care, found to have a code and now unresponsive.

Generalized slowing and frontal alpha.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old woman transferred for cardiogenic shock status post LAD stent, now continuous hemodialysis and possible cardiac arrest.

ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
There is focal slowing continuously seen at F7/T3 throughout the recording.
Generalized slow waves and low amplitude.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing in the left frontal region.
Generalized low amplitude slow waves with lack of reactivity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  78 year old woman status post PEA code for 40 minutes, then 6 minutes in the emergency room, now with episodes of diffuse body shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Atropine, Lasix, Lipitor, Hydralazine, Pantoprazole
REASON FOR STUDY:  Myoclonus.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was unresponsive during the recording.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some sweat artifact and movement artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record has a diffusely slow background in between the bursts that I will describe in the next paragraph.  She has a markedly suppressed background with no clear electrocerebral activity.  However, this is in between much artifact which makes it difficult to make any clear final determinations about electrical activity.  In addition, she has bursts of generalized periodic epileptiform discharges with frontal predominant sharp waves and polyspikes that appear to at times increase in rhythmicity to a frequency of about 4-5 Hz and last for about 30-40 seconds.  During these bursts, which are usually symmetric, but at times slightly asymmetric, the patient appears to be clinically shaking and twitching and jerking.  These are consistent with myoclonic jerks.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  As above.
SEIZURES:  Multiple myoclonic seizures as described above.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frequent myoclonic seizures of prolonged duration in between markedly abnormal suppressed background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical injury and irritability with multiple bursts of generalized periodic discharges and associated jerks consistent with myoclonic seizures.  The interictal pattern as well as the presence of myoclonus in the setting of hypoxic injury suggests a very poor prognosis.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  22 year old right handed female status post spontaneous vaginal delivery on March 8, 2012, presented with episodes of right hand and finger swelling with headaches, confusion, and cough.  She had a seizure 2 weeks ago.  She has a history of epilepsy, Xanax abuse, and concurrently on mask isolation for possible meningitis.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Vancomycin, Ceftriaxone, Metronidazole, Zofran.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures and confusion.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow EEG with a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches, at best, 7 Hz.  It appears to be slightly reactive to eye opening.  There is no normal frontal central beta and the patient appears to show architecture typical for stage I and stage II sleep throughout the recording.  The patient is aroused on a couple of occasions, however, the EEG does not improve markedly in the frequencies.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
There is one transient sharp wave seen maximal at T4, only once in the recording.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Generalized slow waves and a single T4 sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  The one sharp wave seen throughout the recording suggests a possible focus of irritability in the right temporal region which could be seen in patient's with localization related epilepsy.  A repeat recording for a more prolonged period may elucidate a more clear diagnosis.  No seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Continuous intractable seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old woman with history of narcolepsy, sleep apnea, diabetes, intractable seizures, transferred for status, now with recurrent episodes.
MEDICATIONS:  Not mentioned.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed from 03/16/2012 through 03/17/2012 for a period of 14 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with anterior temporal, single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  All events were reviewed using continuous spike detection software as well as seizure detection software and patient along with nurse-reported events.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz and is reactive to eye opening.  There is no __________ central beta.  The patient reaches stages I, II, III, IV and REM sleep during the recording, however, there are multiple arousals throughout the night.  No intercurrent procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focused slow wave seen independently at T3 and T4 occasionally throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
EVENTS:  On 03/17/2012 at 6:00 a.m. the patient is aroused by the nurse to take vitals when she suddenly turns her head to the right, her left arm and right arm become stiff and start trembling irregularly.  She is unresponsive to verbal commands and continues to shake her upper body for about 2-3 minutes, afterwards she subsides, coughs and later on starts again minutes later.  One of the residents comes to see her, and she continues to do this behavior for about 20-25 minutes and then calms and falls asleep.  During this entire episode, the EEG does not reveal any epileptiform activity and has a normal awake background.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to independent bilateral slow waves.  In addition, the captured episode described above had no EEG correlate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  33 year old female with a history of mental retardation and cerebral palsy and seizure disorder.  She had about 8 seizures in school today.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin, Ativan.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture and no activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves were seen in multiple places including F4, T3, P3, T5 intermittently.  In addition, there were runs of frontally predominant polyspikes and waves that at times are left more than right predominant.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts seen throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse slow waves.
Multifocal spikes and frontally predominant polyspikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy with multiple focus for generation of seizures.  In addition, there is
evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  16 year old right handed female with past medical history of pneumonia, complications from ventilator with episode of being scared and looking around without memory.
MEDICATIONS:  Clonidine, Lovenox, Ativan, Melatonin, Morphine, Protonix, Calcium, Iron, Lactobacillus, Sodium Chloride.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Episode of confusion.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in sleep mainly.  Photic stimulation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a background that at best reaches 8-9 Hz, however, the patient mainly and quickly falls asleep in less than a minute.  It is noted that she is in stage 2 sleep.  There are no abnormalities with photic stimulation and no other abnormalities are noted.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Mild excessive theta in wakefulness.  Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts seen for limited periods of time during wakefulness.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  Please note that this recording was mainly in sleep and the limited wakefulness that was captured, the patient quickly into drowsiness and it is possible that part of this mild abnormality may be due to short latency of sleep.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  If a sleep disorder is clinically considered, further evaluation by a sleep specialist may be of help.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  33 year old female with a history of severe MR, cerebral palsy, and seizures, with multiple seizures today.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin, Ativan.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Recurrent seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while awake and asleep.  The record was reviewed using continuous spike detection software as well as seizure detection software and patient noted events, as well as review of the tracings.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture and no activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves were seen in multiple places including F4, T3, P3, and T5 intermittently.  In addition, there were rounds of frontal  polyspikes that at times were more than left and right predominant.
Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 70 microvolts seen throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  Throughout the recording there were 9 tonic seizures noted where the patient suddenly lifted her left and right arms tonically followed by her face opening also in a tonic fashion.  These last for about 15 to 20 seconds and then stop.  In the EEG there appears to be a sudden attenuation seen diffusely throughout the recording consistent with paroxysmal fasts that cannot be localized to one specific region followed by tonic muscle artifact seen throughout the recording and followed by diffuse slowing at the end of the seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
multiple tonic seizures of generalized unclear onset.
multifocal spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy with multiple seizures of unclear onset as well as multiple focus for origination of seizures.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regard to etiology and may be due to the patient's overall cognitive disease.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  78 year old right handed woman with epilepsy who had a funny spell when her face looked funny.  History of palpitations.
MEDICATIONS:  Simvastatin, Oxcarbazepine, Meclizine, ASA, Fluticasone
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This was an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a small amount of shifting slowing.  The overall record is sometimes a bit sharply contoured in the temporal regions.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  Vertex waves and spindles are identified in stage 2 sleep. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response which is present bilaterally.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Mild background slowing.
Occasional shifting slowing greater than accepted for age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Unlike previous EEGs, there were no right temporal sharp waves today.  There was no right temporal significant focal slowing and there were no sharp waves from the left hemisphere. The background slowing and disorganization is a nonspecific finding in an adult of this age and can be seen in the context of underlying cerebrovascular disease or even other comorbidities which may have resulted in the patient's epilepsy.  Please note that previous seizures were characterized by amnestic spells with staring, speech arrest, automatisms, urinary urgency and postictal confusion.  This differs significantly from the event described in the HPI above.

.CLINICAL HISTORY:  72 year old right handed man with a change in mental status and forced right gaze deviation with upper and lower extremity shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lasix, Hydralazine, Minocycline, Fentanyl
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status with right gaze and upper and lower extremity shaking.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some temporal artifact over the left hemisphere.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz.  There is increased amount of beta seen diffusely throughout the recording.  Some sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen at F3 frequently throughout the recording sometimes with a larger field at C3, T3.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left frontal and rarely centroparietal sharp waves.
Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left frontal region or possibly the left centroparietal region.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed female status post cavernoma hemorrhage and craniotomy for right cerebellar cavernoma now with headaches and 1 seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Protonix, Flexeril
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were performed including photic stimulation and hyperventilation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow wave seen at F7/T3 and F8/T4 independently occurring only occasionally at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Independent bitemporal, anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal serial dysfunction in both anterior bitemporal regions, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no abnormal posterior dominant rhythm.  At times there is intermittent central beta seen throughout the recording.  No normal sleep architecture is seen and no activating procedures were performed.  During the recording the patient was stimulated and there was transient muscle artifact seen after the stimulation, but no clear change in the electrocerebral activity.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 mV seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  In this patient it may be due at least in part to medication effect.  During stimulation there was some increase in muscle
artifact, but no clear changes in the cerebral waveforms.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  29 year old man status post assault and decompressive craniotomy with diffuse contusions and no bone flap placed, history of seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a mildly diffuse slow background that at best reaches 7 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some normal frontal central beta.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and stage 1 sleep.

Focal slow waves seen intermittently over the left hemisphere independently at T3, F3, and T3, as well as times independently also over F8/T4.  This is throughout breaching in both regions.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz seen while in wakefulness.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing in the left hemisphere, specifically the mid temporal and frontal, as well as parietal region.
Slowing in the right temporal region,
Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in multiple regions, specifically mainly the left hemisphere and some independently in the right mid temporal region, as well as some diffuse slowing, all of which are nonspecific in regards to etiology, but are likely related to his previous injury.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  63 year old male found unresponsive on April 1st, still not back to baseline, somnolent.  Renal failure, diabetes, hepatitis C, hypertension, nonadherent to medications.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow with a 2-4 Hz background.  It is relatively rhythmic.  There are some sections of the record with an increase in beta activity in the frontal regions.  FIRDA is noted.  Stimulation of the patient produces lower voltage, less rhythmic pattern.
HR:    66 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The picture described above is most compatible with a metabolic pattern.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  43 year old left handed male with oligodendroglioma, diabetes, hyperlipidemia, depression, and VP shunt status post resection with change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed, Keppra, Zonisamide

ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 70 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
There is an associated breach at C3 seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
Focal slowing and breach seen at C3.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  47 year old female with abdominal pain, found to have an MI and had PA code for approximately 40 minutes.  She has a past medical history of CAD, stents, GI bleed, now on ECMO with a temperature of 98.
MEDICATIONS:  Norepinephrine, Epinephrine, Vancomycin, Vasopressor, Heparin.
REASON FOR EEG:  Electric brain dead protocol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode, as well as single lead EMG electrode.  The patient was recorded while comatose and unresponsive.  No activating procedures were performed, other than stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some EKG and ventilator artifact seen intermittently throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to an EEG with no posterior dominant rhythm and no normal background.  There is complete suppression and absence of any normal electrocerebral activity.  There is some intermittent artifact from the EKG and some rare artifact from the ventilator.  The EEG was recorded with an electrocerebral sinus protocol and reviewed at 2 mV with double distance electrodes.  No normal electrical activity was seen.  During the recording the patient's eyes with painful stimulation was performed with no change in the pattern described above.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  No normal electrocerebral activity was seen.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG reveals absence of normal electrocerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with electrocerebral silence.  In the absence of any sedative medications and/or hypothermia it is consistent with lack of any electrical brain activity.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  72 year old right handed woman with seizures on December 6, 2011 characterized by focal motor activity on the left with left sided weakness, past history of stroke, now continues to have difficulty with left sided numbness and a feeling as if her left hand or leg is floating around.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Tramadol, Neurontin, Lisinopril, ASA, Synthroid
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a somewhat slow pattern with an alpha rhythm ranging from 7-8 Hz.  Intermittent focal slowing is noted in the right hemisphere particularly in the central temporal, but sometimes the central occipital regions with disruption of faster frequency activity.  Shifting slowing is noted. Features of drowsiness include an accentuation of focal slowing from the right. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing.
Disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are compatible with a structural process on the right consistent with the previous history of stroke.  No epileptiform features were noted today.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  21 year old right handed female with childhood staring spells and question rolandic seizures in childhood, currently seizure free.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes an reactive 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontal central beta, 8 Hz mu activity is noted, but testing is not performed to confirm this. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing bursts of rhythmic, higher amplitude slowing.  In hyperventilation there appears to be a left mid temporal sharp wave.  Rhythmic and temporal theta is noted as the patient drifts off into sleep.  Frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave activity is noted at approximately 5 Hz as the patient starts to transition in and out stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and POSTS. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant 4-5 Hz spike and wave activity primarily in the transition in and out of sleep.
Left mid temporal sharp wave noted at the end of hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This young adult has previously demonstrated these patterns.  She demonstrates an inherited mechanism for epilepsy.  The focal features were noted in some of her childhood EEGs, but not in the more recent studies.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  74 year old woman with left-sided weakness and slow speech and confusion with 2 episodes of twitching of the left hand and twisting of the lips.
MEDICATIONS:  Famotidine, Probenecid, Hydralazine, Aspirin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Left-sided weakness with twitching of the right hand and lips.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a mildly diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz and can only be seen over the left hemisphere.  Over the left hemisphere, there is normal amount of frontocentral beta, however, none can be seen over the right hemisphere.  Patient appears to be awake and go into stage change of sleep, but the classic sleep architecture is not seen. Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow sharp waves seen periodically in the right hemisphere usually maximal at F8/T4, however, at times more maximal at F8, at times even more maximal at T6 and some of them appear to be maximal at FP2.  These sharp waves were occurring periodically at a frequency of 0.5-1 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts.  The periodicity is consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs).
Focal slow waves in the right hemisphere maximal at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Generalized slow waves at a frequency of 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemisphere periodic lateralized epileptic discharges maximally in the midtemporal region, although with broad field.
Mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of right hemispheric maximal in the midtemporal region, but with a broad field, cortical dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with an acute lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  43 year old left handed male with oligodendroglioma, now with episodes of arm flexion and eyes rolling up in his head.  VP shunt.  Altered mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, Zonisamide, Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a pattern with generous beta.  There are bursts of relatively symmetric theta.  Superimposed on this there is a subtle asymmetry which at times drops out of faster frequency activity on the left.  The record intermittently attenuates and that attenuation may be symmetric.  In the context of a breach rhythm on the left, there are some small discrete left frontotemporal sharp waves.
HR:    144 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A continuous pattern with rhythmic theta followed by brief attenuation.
Generous beta.
An intermittent asymmetry with occasional attenuation on the left.
Occasional to rare lower amplitude discrete left frontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most supportive of an anesthetic pattern for this patient on a propofol drip.  The generous beta may represent the medications
utilized and the brief attenuations can be part of the acute brain process or the medications.  Focal and epileptiform features in this record are quite subtle.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old right handed woman with a seizure in 2006 characterized by feelings of dizziness, nausea, then tonic-clonic activity.  Subsequently, she had paroxysmal dizziness and nausea, but has had no symptoms for 1 year, history of depression.
MEDICATIONS:  Remeron, Dilantin
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  In relaxed wakefulness there is some bursts of shifting slowing, but there is more prominent, left temporal focal slowing with some sharply contoured slowing and even some sharp waves noted in relaxed wakefulness. Hyperventilation seems to accentuate the left temporal focal slowing.  There is wicket activity noted in both temporal regions, but there is also a subtle, underlying left temporal sharp wave.  Later sections of hyperventilation includes some head rocking artifacts. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm, followed by POSTs.  As the patient transitions in and out of a drowsy state, the left anterior temporal focal slowing reappears. Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response.  The patient starts to drift in and out sleep during photic stimulation.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal due to:
Left temporal focal slowing.
Left temporal sharp waves.
Shifting temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Left temporal focal slowing and sharp waves were identified in 2006.  There is some shifting slowing at this time, which may be an age-
related phenomenon.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old woman admitted with left-sided weakness, slurred speech and episodes of twitching of left hand and twitching of the lips.  This is a follow-up EEG.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation is not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized from the left hemisphere.  The right hemisphere intermittently demonstrates significant disruption of faster frequency activity, sharply contoured delta in the right hemisphere and/or spikes or sharp waves in the right hemisphere typically maximum in the temporal regions with variability including T4 and T6.  The vast majority of sharp waves are maximum at T4.  A handful appear a little bit more discreetly at C4 and there is some variability in the sharp waves.  The sharp waves are at times complex starting at F8 and then ending a bit more mid to posterotemporally.  They persist into stage 2 sleep.  As the patient waxes in and out of sleep, some of the sharp waves are right frontal.   Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.  At the close of the record, the patient has some periodic slowing in the right hemisphere.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Slowing in the left hemisphere.
A remarkably vigorous epileptiform focus in the right hemisphere with variable maximum including T4, FT2/4 and even posterotemporal.
Right periodic slowing.
Intermittent to more continuous focal slowing on the right with disruption of faster frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG was compared to a previous study.  The epileptiform activity is no longer a continuous PLED-like pattern, but it is quite prominent.  This continues to supports an ongoing, highly irritative focus.  It is markedly improved, but it remains quite abnormal.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   73 year old woman with a history of left-sided weakness, low speech and confusion with episodes of twitching of the left hand and twisting of the leads on follow up EEG.

There is frontocentral beta seen mainly over the left hemisphere also, not that clearly seen over the right, although there is some.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were not performed.

Focal slowing seen at F7/T3 at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen occasionally.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right temporal slowing.
Attenuation and infrequent sharp waves.
Infrequent left anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cortical structural cerebral dysfunction ______________arising from the right mid=temporal region.  In addition there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region which is non-specific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  64 year old right handed male with a history of seizures, here for evaluation of seizure localization and frequency.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital, Tegretol.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software was used during the EEG.  In addition, patient alarms as well as nurses' notes were also used during the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a mildly diffuse slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches a frequency of 8 Hz, which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen in the left mid-temporal region at T3 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts seen occasionally.
In addition, focal sharp waves are seen infrequently at T3, mainly in sleep.
EVENTS:  At 1:24 in the morning, the patient had an event.  In the video it appears that the patient suddenly becomes agitated and wants to go home.  He stands up abruptly from the bed and starts attacking the nurses and appears to want to stand up and leave.  He stands up out of the bed and disappears from the video.  Minutes later he comes back and he is restrained.  He remains agitated and moves around the bed during the rest of the recording.  During the time the patient becomes agitated and minutes prior becoming agitated, the EEG remains normal with no epileptiform discharges or seizures seen.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal slowing and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy, with seizures likely arising from the left temporal region.  In addition, the episode captured agitation but did not reveal any epileptic discharges and is likely a nonepileptic event.  No seizures were captured during this day 1 of EEG monitoring.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  50 year old male with status epilepticus and bilateral MCA infarcts, right greater than left.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Midazolam, Vancomycin, Zosyn.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is described as poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a significant asymmetry.  The activity from the right is low voltage, relatively featureless.  From the left, there is more theta.  There is also wicket-like rhythm at T1.  There are sharp waves, but they lack after-going slow waves.  The patient is febrile, intubated and poorly responsive.  As the recording continues, the quality of the EEG recording declines as the pace melts off.  Stimulation of the patient produces artifact.  The patient is markedly diaphoretic, but with a temperature of only 99.6.

A slow pattern on the left with prominent wicket, but no definitive sharp waves or spikes.
