CLINICAL HISTORY:  82 year old woman found unresponsive, not moving her right side with 2 tonic-clonic seizures in the emergency room.  Left MCA infarct, multiple medical problems.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed, Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is quite agitated.  There is an extraordinary amount of muscle artifact.  She receives Versed during the EEG with little benefit.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Underneath the muscle and movement artifact, there seems to be a theta frequency background.  Surprisingly, despite the artifacts, there is a periodic complex in the left hemisphere maximum at T1, but with involvement of F7 and T3.  It overall has a generous field of spread throughout the temporal region on the left and the frontal regions.  The periodic complex is seen in approximately every 2 seconds.  It does not evolve.  The patient is talking during the discharge.
HR:    90 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing.
A periodic complex noted on the left temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This was a high amplitude, but relatively simple periodic complex.  It did not evolve.  It is more likely to be a hallmark of an epileptiform process than an active ictal discharge.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed male with post traumatic epilepsy, closed head trauma injury in 1980, atonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is the patient's fourth EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized.  There is some bursts of posterior predominant slowing.  There are also bursts of frontally predominant high amplitude 3 Hz spike and slow wave activity.  This activity demonstrates some asymmetry, maybe a little bit more prominent in the right frontal region on the left.  It starts to transition to more of a 4-5 Hz spike and wave activity.
Although it is present in relaxed wakefulness, it also occurs during hyperventilation.  Most bursts are less than 2 seconds in duration.  No impairment of awareness is noted with the bursts.
As the patient becomes drowsy, following hyperventilation, the bursts are again seen, but are a little bit slower and transition to a more of an almost 3 second burst with a high amplitude frontal spike, followed by rhythmic delta, which may or may not have a spike.  All of the activity has bilateral representation, but some has a field more prominent on the right.
Photic stimulation may well have accentuated this activity and, again, in photic stimulation sometimes there did seem to be a more clearly defined right frontal spike and slow wave complex before the left, but not always.
At the end of the record when the patient is maximally awake, there is little in the way of background slowing.
Even when the EEG is well organized, the alpha rhythm remains low at 8 Hz.
HR:    64 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity, which was accentuated by hyperventilation and photic.
Occasional shifting asymmetries, particularly in the posterior region.
A slow alpha for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are features in this EEG which support a focal mechanism for epilepsy.  Other features support a generalized mechanism, particularly with 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity, which was accentuated by hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  This suggests more than one possible contributor to this patient's epilepsy.
Of note, some of these findings were seen in an EEG in March 2011, but not in October 2010 or September 2011.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  82 year old woman admitted one week after 2 seizures with right hemiparesis, now found on floor unable to move the right side.  The patient had been incontinent.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is cooperative and in fact somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates an asymmetry.  There is primarily a theta and beta pattern from the right.  The left hemisphere demonstrates significant disruption of faster frequency activity.  There are relatively frequent sharp waves noted from the left hemisphere, including F7, T1, or FP1.  On occasions these appear as bursts. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster frequency activity on the right.  At 3:15 p.m. there is a burst of spike activity, but no clinical features are noted.  Testing is not performed during that burst.
HR:    108 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked slowing from the left hemisphere.
A seizure at 03:15:31.  When reviewed at slow paper speed this discharge of 24 seconds duration meets the electrographic criteria for a single seizure.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates a clearly epileptiform pattern.  The findings described above can be seen in the context of any irritative process,
including status epilepticus, focal lesion, or herpes encephalitis.  Consequently, clinical correlation is essential.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  50 year old man with bilateral large MCA infarcts and previous status.

There appears to be some theta frequency seen only throughout the left hemisphere and being absent over the right hemisphere.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.

Focal slow waves seen intermittently at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-50 mV.

Left temporal focal slow waves.
Generalized slow waves.
Right hemispheric diffuse attenuation.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old man with MS and recurrent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 30-year-old man status post cranioplasty today with shaking and suspected seizures with a history of TBI and assault and a history of seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, Versed, Dilantin, Lamictal.

No normal sleep architecture was seen and no activating procedures were performed.
Abnormal discharges:
There are focal slow waves seen continuously at F7/T3 and intermittently at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
In addition, over the right hemisphere there is an increase of the number of faster frequencies that cannot be clearly seen over the left hemisphere.
Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts.
Lastly, please note at times a posterior dominant rhythm can be seen over the right hemisphere only  which at best reaches 6 Hz.
One focal sharp transient was seen at C4.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to continuous left hemispheric maximum anterior temporal slowing and intermittent right anterior temporal slowing with loss of faster frequencies over the left hemisphere, in addition to generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction involving white and gray matter in the left hemisphere, maximal in the anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right anterior temporal region in addition to generalized cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.  The sharp transient seen at C4 is of unclear significance and further recording will help in elucidating its significance.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  27 year old gentleman with mitochondrial disease, MELAS, refractory epilepsy, cardiomyopathy, admitted with recurrent salaam seizures characterized by flexion of the left arm in an almost purposeful manner, elevation of the right arm and stiffening.  No new other medical issues.  This is the patient's first status epilepticus in 2 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Dilantin, Ativan, Klonopin, Topamax
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was obtunded with frequent seizures.  He did not appear to be interactive to outside stimuli.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow, featureless low voltage with delta and smaller amounts of beta. Frequent seizures were recorded.  Electrographic discharges were typically 5-7 seconds in duration and included mixed frequency, generalized paroxysmal fast activity which was frontally predominant.  Typically, it was not until the third second of the electrographic discharge that the patient had the behavioral correlate with flexion of the left arm, stiffening of the right and tonic posturing.   Based on these results, the patient was placed on long term video EEG monitoring and pharmacotherapy was initiated.  This EEG is diagnostic of a generalized form of status epilepticus.
HR:   N/A
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly abnormal background.
Bursts of paroxysmal fast activity with associated clinical seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The bursts of paroxysmal fast activity described in this EEG differs from previous EEGs.  This may represent a new seizure pattern for this individual or maturation of a pre-existing or interictal pattern.  He previously had frontal spike and wave activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed man with history of epilepsy since 2005 with complex partial seizures and secondary tonic-clonic seizures, a past medical history of high cholesterol, depression and anxiety.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Zonisamide, Tegretol
REASON FOR STUDY:  Recurrent seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal sharp waves seen at F7/T3 as well as infrequently at F8/T4 mainly during sleep.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left more than right anterior temporal sharp waves occurring occasionally.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from either anterior temporal region.  No seizures were seen.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  1 hour and 2 minutes
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 25-year-old man with past medical history of drug abuse, now found down by wife with needle in the arm in the bathroom after being alone for about 2 minutes.  Pulseless electrical activity was documented in the field.  The patient was later revived.  Now the patient is with generalized myoclonic jerks concerning for status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan and vecuronium is given later during the exam.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  From the beginning of the recording until approximately 02:46:30 p.m. EEG consists of diffuse multiple artifact. This makes evaluation of the underlying EEG activity unreliable.
At approximately 02:46:20 p.m., 10 mg of vecuronium is administered.  EEG artifact subsequently disappears within about 10-20 seconds.  Subsequent record demonstrates low-to-moderate amplitude theta and delta activity with posterior under-riding frequencies, without posterior dominant rhythm or anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  No abnormal sleep architecture is present.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation was not performed.  Sinus tachycardia is captured on the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Disorganization.
Symmetry.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal greater than 1-hour EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing and thus disorganization.  These findings indicate nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction, that in this patient could partially be related to the medication effect.  No electrographic seizures are captured.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team and to the neurology consult team at the time of the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  47 year old female with a history of seizures, depression, husband, here for seizures.

REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures.

ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen in the left hemisphere, maximal at times at F7 and other times at T3.  These are seen at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts, very frequently throughout the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  82 year old right handed woman with a left-sided lesion in May with right hemiparesis and 2 episodes of incontinence.  Multiple seizures recorded May 13.  The patient had a craniotomy 4 weeks ago, was evaluated at the University of Pennsylvania earlier this month for recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Keppra, Depakote, Dilantin, Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is at times poorly organized and bilaterally slow.  In other sections, there is a more significant asymmetry with a pattern on the right that is only mildly slow and an alpha rhythm of 8 Hz on the right.  The alpha rhythm tends to be slower on the left, and there is disruption of faster frequency activity on the left with occasional sharp waves.  Features of drowsiness include more of a bilateral background slow pattern and shifting slowing. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is confused.  There is scant driving on the right.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the left with disruption of faster frequency activity and arrhythmic delta activity.
Occasional sharp waves in the left hemisphere, particularly the temporal region.
Background slowing on the right which is variable, sometimes only moderately slow.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this individual.  She has previously been evaluated for repetitive seizures.  The right hemisphere may be a little bit slower than in the past, but the left hemisphere is not quite as remarkably slow.  These findings can be compared to the long-term monitoring and follow-up EEGs from May 2012.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old man found down unresponsive.  CT with a right MCA stroke.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  No activating procedures were performed.  No normal sleep architecture was seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-50 microvolts were continuously throughout the recording.

Generalized slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old right handed woman with depression, anxiety, schizophrenia and epilepsy.  Seizures are characterized by shaking with tongue biting and incontinence, last seizure was 1 week ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, Risperdal, Risperidone
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is excess theta in apparent wakefulness.  There is sometimes a background of more rhythmic theta.
Interictal findings for this individual include frontal fast activity, right more so than the left with a subtle frontal sharp wave underlying and a sharp wave can be seen at  Fp2-F4 with a small amount of bilateral representation.  Rare, higher amplitude left mid temporal sharp waves were identified.
Hyperventilation was performed early in the record producing rhythmic slowing particularly in the frontal regions.  The hyperventilation response included some arrhythmic slowing.  Features of drowsiness included slow rolling eye movements, slowing of  the alpha rhythm, and increase in overall background slowing, but deeper stages of sleep were not sustained. Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frontal fast activity with a right frontal underlying sharp wave.
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy and raises the possibility of more than one mechanism for seizures.  Left anterior temporal sharp waves, right temporal sharp waves and bifrontal sharp waves were noted in a previous EEG in 2008.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  69 year old man with history of a right MCA stroke as well as AFib, CHF, and hyperlipidemia that presents with an episode of possible syncope with shaking of the head for a few minutes.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, Lipitor, Tramadol, Warfarin, Digoxin, Amlodipine, Metoprolol.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which can be best visualized over the left hemisphere.  There is also frontocentral beta that can only be seen over the left hemisphere.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  Some of the sleep architecture was best observed only over the left hemisphere.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at F8/T4.
Focal slow waves were seen continuously over the right hemisphere, maximal at F8/T4.  There was also loss of faster frequencies over this hemisphere.
Focal slow waves seen intermittently at F7/T3.
HR:   80 bpm and irregular
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right anterior temporal sharp waves and slowing with loss of faster frequencies.
Intermittent left anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy, with seizures likely arising from the right anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal structural dysfunction in the right hemisphere, maximal in the right anterior temporal region, which is consistent with the known stroke.  Lastly, there is some evidence of left anterior temporal slowing, focal cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old male admitted September 3, with hypoxic respiratory failure, found down with right MCA infarct, persistent obtundation, now weaning off the ventilator.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Depakote, Vancomycin, Albumin, Valproate, Pantoprazole, Zosyn
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a mixed frequency background, but with generalized slowing and a mixture of delta and theta.  There are some shifting asymmetries, but the overall pattern is relatively symmetric.  When the patient is reactive, there is eye movement and a bit more faster frequency activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in delta.  There are rare sections of the record with a bit more focal slowing with attenuation of faster frequency in the right frontocentral region.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Rare sections of the record with more well-defined focal slowing characterized by disruption of faster frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This study is very similar to the previous study September 4th .  The overall pattern is more compatible with a diffuse cerebral insult as might be anticipated with hypoxic anoxic injury.  If additional information is needed, somatosensory evoked potentials may be valuable for a prognosis.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  54 year old left handed female with multiple meningioma status post resection in 2001, simple partial seizures with facial twitching.  Seizure free since 2004.
MEDICATIONS:  Carbatrol, Estrace, Lisinopril, HCTZ, Amlodipine, Calcium
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  The patient has a previous craniotomy on the left.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage, frontocentral beta.  A prominent breach rhythm is identified in the left frontocentral region.  Subtle, underlying focal slowing is noted.  There are also bursts of somewhat higher amplitude slowing noted in the left frontocentral region.  As the patient becomes somewhat drowsy, there is a bit of shifting slowing, some of which includes T3 and T5.  The underlying slowing may be subtle or may include a bit more arrhythmic delta, which may be frontal or occasionally mid to posterior temporal. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. Hyperventilation accentuates the bursts of focal slowing from the left.  During hyperventilation, there is some head rocking or electrode artifact noted, a bit more on the left.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing noted in the left hemisphere with 2 types of focal slowing, the first being underlying subtle slowing and the second being more well-defined arrhythmic delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A breach rhythm is an anticipated finding following craniotomy.  There is some sharply contoured activity on the left in the region of the breach, but there are no definitive sharp waves.  This EEG is similar to many previous EEGs dating to 2002, but of note, in more recent years left mid-temporal sharp waves have not been identified.  In the past, sharp waves included T1, T3, and T5.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  27 year old man known to Neuro with a  previous history of mitochondrial disease, MELAS, refractory epilepsy, cardiomyopathy, recurrent seizures characterized by flexion of the arm, elevation of the right arm and stiffening.  Also, a history of status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Topamax, Clonazepam, Lisinopril, Vimpat, Dilantin, Norvasc, Metoprolol
REASON FOR EGG:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while asleep mainly.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens with the patient in sleep, mainly in Stage II with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontocentral beta seen.  In between the recording the patient develops paroxysm bursts of fast activity which appears to be diffusely seen and mixed with myogenic artifact. It is difficult to piece out the electric serial activity from the myogenic artifact, but clearly occurs paroxysmally in bursts lasting up to 20 to 21 seconds.  During this event there is no clear changes that can be seen on the EEG and in the latter halves of the bursts there appears to be some rhythmic theta-like activity.  Frontal theta predominant consistent with some frontal slowing.  Otherwise, the patient is recorded mainly in sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Bursts of polyspike generalized discharges lasting for a second.
Generalized slowing, absence of normal EEG architecture even during wakefulness.
SEIZURES:
The above described episodes of generalized polyspike and fast followed intermixed with myogenic artifact and followed by some frontal theta consistent with generalized seizures.  However, clinically there are no clear behavioral changes seen on the video.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized seizures.
Polyspike discharges.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of generalized epilepsy with multiple seizures seen during the recording.  No normal awake activity was seen, but mainly the patient was recorded with intermittent sleep.  It is suggested to have continued recording of this individual as the seizures are treated]

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 45-year-old woman, admitted yesterday with hepatic encephalopathy, ammonia level of 200, this morning ammonia level down to 27.  CT with diffuse edema and hypodensity in the left parietal and occipital regions.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan drip, piperacillin, Zosyn, albuterol, fentanyl.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the lab in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was intubated and comatose.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a markedly slow pattern with a mixture of delta and theta.  There were sections of the record when the patient had eye opening.
This EEG demonstrates a dynamic pattern.  There are spontaneous arousals with a pattern rich in delta and theta frequency activity.  There are also sections of the record with much more slow delta.  Intermittent attenuations were noted.  There are rare triphasic waves.
Tactile stimulation of the patient produced an attenuation of the background.
A single left anterior temporal sharp wave was noted.
Heart rate:  100 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly abnormal background with a slow pattern.
A variable pattern sometimes with slow featureless delta, but with spontaneous arousals, although still a slow pattern.
Rare triphasic waves.
Intermittent attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The pattern described above is a nonspecific finding, but supports a diffuse encephalopathy.  The triphasic waves are compatible with a metabolic encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 65-year-old woman with diabetes and possible left MCA stroke, admitted in DKA, the patient began to arouse and was re-sedated.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan drip, vancomycin, ceftriaxone, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient's Ativan drip was reduced just prior to the EEG.

Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an arousal.
The arousal includes an increase in theta.
There is a subtle asymmetry with a bit more slow delta in the right posterior quadrant.
Heart rate 120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of a normal background with primarily a beta frequency pattern.
A low voltage slow pattern.
A subtle asymmetry with a bit more delta in the right posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings described above are most compatible with a pharmacologic coma, the asymmetry described above should be correlated with repeat imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old with right MCA infarct in 2009, left hemiparesis, drug and alcohol abuse, admitted after recurrent tonoclonic seizures after alcohol and drug ingestion.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital, Thiamine, Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent, but with brief arousals.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  With arousals, a low voltage, well-defined awake pattern is noted from the left with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm. The right hemisphere demonstrates intermittent, arrhythmic delta.  Vertex waves, K-complexes and spindles are noted in stage II sleep.
This is a dynamic pattern, as the recording continues, occasional frontal spikes are noted more so on the right than the left.  In addition, the focal slowing and the generalized background slowing is more prominent in the initial sections of the record.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the right hemisphere.
Right frontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The focal slowing and the sharp waves are ipsilateral to the patient's stroke.  This EEG supports a
focal mechanism for the patient's seizures.  This is a dynamic, postictal pattern with a more awake individual at the end of the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63-year-old woman with a past history of stroke, rare complex partial seizures with colorful characterization of complex partial seizures now with jerking of arms and face, involuntary jerking of right arm and face can be increased by stimulation.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  During the EEG, the patient has right face and hand stimulus sensitive jerking.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is challenging.  There is generous beta noted throughout.  There is also a fair amount of movement and muscle artifact.  Periodic complexes are noted from the left hemisphere with where the pattern of periodic delta with a positive sharp at T1 in association with the patient's involuntary jerking.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Clinical jerking on the right associated more with the pattern of periodic delta and sharp-wave spikes, left posterior temporal.
Focal delta from the left hemisphere.
Background disorganization on the right.
Excess beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most compatible with an epilepsy partialis continua pattern.  Based on this with EEG recording, long-term EEG monitoring was initiated.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 65-year-old woman with past medical history of diabetes, hypertension and new onset seizure on 09/25/2012.  Seizure was described as loss of consciousness followed by a generalized tonic clonic convulsion.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, lisinopril, lovastatin, metformin, ranitidine, Advair, Lantus.
INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm reaches 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep symmetrical vertex waves and sleep spindles are captured.  Intermittent bursts of polymorphic theta and delta activity are captured over the right temporal region.  Intermittently this slowing is rhythmic in the delta range (TIRDA; temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity).  No clear epileptiform discharges are captured.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in occipital driving that is better pronounced over the left.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent mild to moderate left temporal slowing.
TIRDA (temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 22 minute awake and asleep EEG due to intermittent mild to moderate right temporal slowing that is often rhythmic.  This finding indicates focal right temporal dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  Finding of rhythmic activity over the right temporal region may indicate potential epileptogenic focus over that region.  No clear epileptiform discharges are captured.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not exclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 82-year-old woman with metastatic cancer, cerebral metastasis found unresponsive, not able to move the right side and then had 2 tonic clonic seizures.

Heart rate 90 BPM.

Continuous arrhythmic delta activity from the left hemisphere.
Sharp waves in the left hemisphere with some variability including T3, C3 and T5.
Bihemispheric background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The bihemispheric slowing may be due to post ictal state or bihemispheric diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  The focal slowing on the left and epileptiform activity may be correlated with imaging.  No seizures were recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 40-year-old woman with history of HIV, seizure disorder, cocaine abuse, presented after falling and fractured her left femur.  EEG to rule out seizures.  Follow up from October 25, no new seizure activity reported.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and drowsy.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a background that at best reaches a posterior dominant of 9 Hz.  However, the overall background appears to be intermixed with frontal maximal delta discharges that appear to reach all the way to the occipital region and seen intermittently and rhythmically.  In addition, at times there is less faster frequencies seen over the right hemisphere than the left in the frontal regions.  There is no normal sleep architecture.
Activating procedures, including hyperventilation, accentuates the frontal slowing which I will describe later.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen in the prefrontal regions, mainly FP1 and PF2, almost continuously throughout the recording at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
At times there is also frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity seen in bursts, also noted FIRDA.
There is also some left frontal temporal slowing at F7/T3 seen intermittently at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to continuous prefrontal slowing, as well as some left frontal temporal slowing.  In addition, there is some intermittent frontal FIRDA activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the prefrontal regions, in addition to the left frontal temporal or anterior temporal regions, which may be related to known previous trauma.  In addition, there is evidence of frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to medication effect or metabolic encephalopathy, although these findings can be very nonspecific.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen which is different to the previous EEG which had noted some left anterior temporal or left temporal sharp waves.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG.
DIAGNOSES:  Memory problems, forgetfulness, and agitation.
HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old right-handed woman with past medical history significant for dementia and asthma, who presents for worsening of forgetfulness and agitation.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  These tracing captures wakefulness through short period of drowsiness.  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9 to 9.5 hertz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude, seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye-blink artifacts.  There are intermittent periods of bitemporal slowing at F7/T3 and F8/T4 during wakefulness and short period of drowsiness consisting of 3 hertz delta frequency, 50-60 microvolt in amplitude lasting 1-2 seconds.  Hyperventilation resulted in slowing seen in most cerebral hemispheres.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple fresh frequencies and resulting in a driving response.  Heart rate was 70-80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to bitemporal slowing during wakefulness and short period of drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of bilateral structural abnormalities or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  Other causes included toxic metabolic or infectious encephalopathy, or degenerative causes.  There were no epileptiform abnormalities or seizures noted during this study.  The abscess of epileptiform abnormalities does not exclude to possibility of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If seizure remains a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing either stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 30-year-old male with diabetes, confusion, fever, and shortness of breath; evaluate for encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Vancomycin, antibiotics, clonidine, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a bedside recording performed on a patient who is confused.  The overall background is slow.  At times, there is a glimpse of an 8 Hz alpha rhythm, but most of the background is a mixture of theta with a smaller amount of beta.  The 8 Hz alpha rhythm clearly attenuates with eye opening, and much of the record includes more of a low to medium amplitude theta pattern with occasional rhythmic delta.  The patient is drowsy, yawning with some hypersynchronous rhythmic theta.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Rhythmic slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most characteristic of an encephalopathy.  There were brief sections of the record with an alerting with an 8 Hz alpha rhythm.
There were no focal or epileptiform features identified. If seizure is an important indication, a followup study in the lab may be of use.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Unresponsiveness status post code.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old woman with known thyroid cancer discovered 15 years ago with progressive dysphagia who had emergency surgery remove mass.  She became acutely bradycardic.  She had CPR started and coded for about 12 minutes.  She had a change in mental status after the code.
MEDICATIONS:  Zofran, albuterol, insulin, Ancef, sodium chloride, chlorhexidine, __________, magnesium oxide, amiodarone, Tylenol, Protonix, vitamin K, Zosyn, vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There was a 60 Hz artifact seen in the F1 and F2 electrodes throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There was no normal sleep architectural and no activating procedures were performed.  Overall, the background was consistent with a diffuse delta pattern at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude 20-40 microvolts.  __________ there is frontal by frontal slowing and sharp waves seen frequently throughout the recording.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Bifrontal and sometimes central sharp waves seen at CZ, F3 and F4, and at times at FP1 or FP2.
Focal slowing in the bifrontal region.
Generalized slowing as described before.
SEIZURES:  At 1:21 p.m. the EEG recording suddenly stopped and the recording restarts at 1:24 p.m.  At this point there is a clear prefrontal rhythmic discharge consistent of sharp waves maximal mainly at FP1, but at times at FP2 at a frequency of 3-4 Hz going on continuously with no clear clinical correlate.  This pattern is consistent with an electrographic seizure.  The electrographic seizure continues without stopping until about almost 19 minutes later after receiving Ativan at 1:39 p.m.  After that the EEG appears to go back to a diffusely slow background with some prefrontal slowing.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to an electrographic prefrontal maximal seizure with no clear onset seen as well as bifrontal slowing and generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals electrographic seizures which appears to be maximally in the frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the frontal region as well as diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but is likely related to the hypoxic injury.  These findings were discussed with the team and the patient will be placed on long-term monitoring.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63-year-old woman with a history of asthma, hypertension, diabetes, hyperlipidemia, left subarachnoid cerebral hemorrhage in 2009 with right residual weakness, __________ stroke in 2009 who presents with seizures and 2 in the ER.

MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital, Ativan, atenolol, nifedipine, Bactrim, insulin, pravastatin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact seen at times.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  The patient was recorded mainly while drowsy.  There is some sleep architecture that can be seen.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Overall the background consists of delta frequency, slowing seen diffusely with some variability up on stimulation.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at 01 and at times at T5/P3.  Frequently throughout the recording at times the sharp waves become rhythmic and occurred at a frequency of 1-2 Hz and then they start and stop.
Focal slowing seen in the posterior quadrant in the area of 01/T5/P3.  This slowing at times is rhythmic but does not  clearly evolve or appear to be epileptic.
Diffuse slowing seen at a frequency of 2-4 Hz, amplitude 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left occipital and posterior temporal parietal sharp waves as well as almost continuous focal slowing and generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left occipital or posterior temporal parietal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral structural dysfunction in the left posterior quadrant, which may be related to the previous hemorrhage.  Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effect.  No seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 46-year-old woman with recurrent left MCA infarcts, status post pial synangiosis, developed left subdural hemorrhage and was found to have epilepsia partialis continua with right arm shaking, twitching episodes.  This is a follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is seen, this is nicely seen and is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta which is slightly higher in amplitude over the left hemisphere.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded during stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen frequently at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to frequent left mid temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal dysfunction in the left mid temporal region which is consistent with a known history of stroke and surgery.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges are seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 19-year-old woman status post MVA with multiple fractures and pneumothorax, traumatic brain injury.  Initial CT demonstrated cerebral edema.  Follow up CT demonstrated improvement.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilaudid, propofol drip, fentanyl drip, Benadryl, Ativan, ceftriaxone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This was a technically challenging EEG due to the patient's matted hair and encrusted blood.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a markedly slow pattern with slow delta and some faster frequency activity.  The patient is somewhat interactive despite the background slowing and the technologist reports that with stimulation the patient will move the right hand to command.
There is a small amount of faster frequency activity noted in the frontal regions, as well as slow frontal delta.
Heart rate:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging, but markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
Shifting slowing with a bit more rhythmic delta noted with stimulation on the left compared to the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  On the whole this EEG supports a severe bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function with shifting asymmetries, but no specific lateralization.  Although the patient appeared to be responsive to the family, the responsive was difficult to identify.  No epileptiform features were identified.  Given the number of sedative hypnotic medications utilized, medications may play a significant role in the pattern described above.

DIAGNOSIS:  Altered mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 57-year-old man with history of cirrhosis admitted for abdominal pain.  He has been unresponsive since 11/21/2012.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include propofol, rifaximin, vancomycin, lactulose.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in ICU using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to two T1-T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captures the patient in a comatose state, sedated state.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the comatose/sedated state, there was seen diffuse attenuation of the background with intermittent EKG artifacts.  There was unknown artifact in bilateral frontoparietal regions likely due to a ventilators.  There was seen very low voltage 1.5 Hz delta frequency activity and occasional 3 Hz delta frequency activity of 5-10 microvolt amplitude.  There was seen no spontaneous variability and reactivity on stimulating the patient.  No seizures or epileptiform activity was seen during this recording.  Heart rate was 80-90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing the patient in a comatose/sedative state due to diffuse slowing and attenuation of the background.  No seizures or epileptiform activity was seen during this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing and attenuation of the background are suggestive of severe anoxic encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to severe metabolic or infectious encephalopathy or due to effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  In addition, diffuse attenuation could be seen in bilateral fluid collection in the extra-axial space or the overlying skull.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or of intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 73-year-old woman who presents with episodes of loss of consciousness and generalized stiffness lasting for 5 minutes with confusion.  She has working diagnosis of Hashimoto's encephalitis due to rapidly progressive dementia.  Currently on steroids.
MEDICATIONS:  Risperdal, levothyroxine, famotidine, Keppra, steroids.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some frontal electrode artifact seen frequently throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The records opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
Overall the background consisting of diffusely slow delta 2-4 Hz frequency discharge, which is intermixed with some theta frequency discharge.  In addition, there are frequent anterior predominant deflections with an anterior to posterior lag most consistent with triphasic waves seen frequently, at times rhythmically, in a pseudoperiodic fashion.  In addition, there are intermittent focal sharp waves seen over the left hemisphere at T3, sometimes at F7 and sometimes at T5, and independently over the right hemisphere at T4 and sometimes at F8/T4.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  Regular at 84 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to multifocal left hemisphere and right hemisphere sharp waves, as well as triphasic discharges and generalized slow disorganized background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multifocal cortical irritability, as well as generalized diffuse cerebral dysfunction, all of which may be seen with a diffuse cortical process suggestive of an encephalitis or rapidly progressive neurologic degenerative disease.  Some of the findings may also be due to a metabolic disturbance.  No clear seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Status post code.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old woman, status post partial thyroidectomy, was in status post code, rule out ECS per request, propofol was given before EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, Ativan, vancomycin, Coumadin, Dilantin, metoprolol, Protonix, insulin, and albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while fully responsive or obtunded.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Continuous P4 artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  Overall the background is consistent with adult slow wave pattern at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-40 mV.  At times there is some intermixed frontal beta seen intermittently throughout the recording.
The patient was stimulated with verbal, as well as tactile stimuli and painful stimuli.  With painful stimuli there appears to be a diffuse muscle discharge seen in all the electrodes.  However, there is no increase in the frequencies overall in the EEG.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  150.
Abnormal discharges:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-30 mV with some muscle reactivity, but no major frequency reactivity and some variability in the EEG.
During the beginning of the recording the patient appears to have some head jerking movements towards the right and towards the left intermittently, however, the EEG did not reveal any clear electrographic correlate to these movements.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to marked generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  However, the intermittent frontal beta suggested it may be due at least in part to medication effect.  The jerking movements appear in the video to be more consistent with myoclonus, however, there was no electrographic correlate to them. No clear seizures or epileptiform activity was seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63-year-old female with a past medical history of asthma, hypertension, diabetes, hyperlipidemia, and left subarachnoid with intracerebral hemorrhage, with right-sided residual weakness as well as a cerebellar stroke in 2009, presents with seizures; in the ER had 2 more.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital, topiramate.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded awake and drowsy.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that, at best, reaches 6 to 7 Hz and is seen best over the right hemisphere.  There is no normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.  Overall, the background consists of diffusely slow theta rhythm, seen best over the right hemisphere and not well over the left hemisphere.  There appears to be some state changes, but no typical or classic sleep architecture.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at O1 and sometimes at O2 in wakefulness and drowsiness.
Focal slow waves seen over the left hemisphere, maximal in the mid to posterior temporal region.
Generalized slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts, seen continuously throughout the recording.
Heart rate:  66.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left occipital sharp waves as well as left posterior temporal/mid-temporal focal slowing attenuation, in addition to generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left occipital region.  In addition, there is evidence of left posterior temporal and mid-temporal focal cerebral dysfunction, which is consistent with the known previous hemorrhage.  Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 23-year-old gentleman with past gunshot wound to the head 5 years ago. Tonic clonic seizures lasting 2-3 minutes; last seizure 2 months ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed. This is a neurologically disabled adult in a supported wheelchair.  The patient is described as markedly drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow with diffuse delta noted.  There is a breach rhythm on the left with higher amplitude, sharply contoured delta with a broad field of spread at T3.  There is also electrode pop and irregular delta or focal delta in the right posterior region, T6-L2, and sometimes C4.  As the patient drifts off to sleep there is a small increase in beta.  There are also a handful of more triangular shaped higher amplitude right frontal delta waves.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for photoelectric artifact, but no significant driving.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Paucity of the normal wave forms for an adult.
Replacement of normal background with delta.
Sharply contoured delta noted from either hemisphere including left mid temporal, right posterior or right frontocentral.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.  No seizures were recorded.  Although breach rhythm is suggested with higher amplitude delta on the left, epileptiform activity is seen from both hemispheres independently.  This EEG is slower than previous studies, but there is less epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 42-year-old woman with paranoid schizophrenia and new episodes of intermittent left arm jerking and twitching.  Now with right arm jerking.
MEDICATIONS:  Prozac, Zocor, clozapine, Cogentin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were both completed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10-Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of background theta.  The EEG is slightly disorganized.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in background slowing.  Features of drowsiness include a small amount of frontal theta and a decrease in eye movement.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  Heart rate is 90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
A small amount of background theta.
A small amount of disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The features described above are nonspecific, but can be seen in the context of the use of CNS acting medications.  If epilepsy is an important consideration a follow up study capturing this patient's behaviors may be of value.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Portable EEG.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 19-year-old female with history of TBI on 11/09/2012 and multiple problems in surgical ICU status post tracheostomy.  She had first-time seizure yesterday described as eye twitching and questionable right facial droop, lasting less than 1 minute witnessed by mom who is a nurse at the hospital.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Ativan as needed, morphine, Keppra, Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  A bedside digital EEG was performed in the ICU using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1-channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captures the patient in a sedated and confused state.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This was a technically limited study due to electrode placement and diffusely attenuated recording.  In a sedated state, there was attenuated background consisting of 5-6 Hz theta frequency intermixed with alpha activity and also beta frequency.  There were bursts of sleep spindles diffusely with diffuse distribution noted.  There was burst of rapid eye movement artifact noted on several occasions during drowsiness.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures noted during this recording.  Heart rate was 100-120 and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically limited, but abnormal EEG recording capturing the patient in a sedated state due to 1 absence of posterior dominant rhythm and slowing and attenuation of background activity, intermixed with sleep spindles in bursts.  No epileptiform activity or seizures were captured in this study.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of metabolic, toxic, anoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures were captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or of intermittent seizures.  Diffuse beta activity can be seen due to effect of sedative medications include barbiturate or benzodiazepines.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG with better electrode placement is recommended.

STUDY DATE:  01/14/2013 to 01/15/2013 for a total of 15 hours.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 53-year-old woman with recurrent seizures despite multiple medications here for seizure differential and classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, zonisamide.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, stage 1, stage 2 and deeper stages of sleep including REM.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves at F7/T3 and F8/T4 (Left > Right) seen intermittently in wakefulness and sleep.
EPISODES OR EVENTS:  None.
SEIZURES:
None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral (left more than right) anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen in day 1 of recording.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  Nearly 22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 50-year-old woman status post cardiac arrest on 11/09/2012 for 12 minutes.  Status post cardiac arrest, the patient was in status epilepticus.  The patient is currently with fevers.
MEDICATIONS:  Include Keppra, insulin, Lopressor, Coumadin, Synthroid, etc.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of nearly continuous frequent high amplitude diffuse EMG artifact that corresponds to teeth grinding.  During brief periods of EEG that do not contain this artifact, the background appears to consist of diffuse polymorphic theta and delta activity.  Multiple electrodes have high impedances due to poor patient cooperation with the exam.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  No normal sleep architecture is observed.  Heart rate of approximately 120 beats a minute is observed on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Nearly continuous teeth grinding artifact.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake only 22-minute EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing. This finding indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction. However, the majority of the recording was obscured by frequent teeth grinding artifact, and epileptiform discharges could have been missed.  If clinically indicated, a repeat study with less artifact may be of benefit.  Tachycardia is noted on the single EKG lead.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 58-year-old woman with septic shock, multisystem failure.
MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, vasopressin, dopamine, heparin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient was intubated and was in contact isolation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly low voltage, slow and featureless.  It includes a pattern with slow, low voltage delta and intermittent attenuation.  Stimulation of the patient does not significantly activate the record, although there is some variability with some sections with a bit more continuous delta and small amounts of theta.
Heart rate 120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
Intermittent attenuations of suppressions.
Absence of reactivity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  To place this EEG in the appropriate clinical context, the severity of the patient's multisystem injuries should be known, but this EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function which may be toxic, metabolic and/or related to
this patient's multisystem failure.  This EEG carries a worrisome prognosis, but again, must be placed in the appropriate clinical context.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 55-year-old female presents on 01/18/2013 with history of PEA code for 25 minutes.  Past medical history is significant for fall 2 weeks ago, hypertension, and nonischemic cardiomyopathy, ethanol abuse.  Patient was recorded with concern for status epilepticus versus a nonconvulsive status epilepticus.  She was recorded in an unresponsive, unarousable state.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using a standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  The patient was recorded in an unresponsive, unarousable state.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There was no cerebral brain activity noted throughout this recording.  This recording was not arranged for brain death protocol. In different montages including average differential and with a sensitivity of 2 microvolt, there was no cerebral activity noted.  There was no spontaneous variability or stimulation reactivity were noted.  Heart rate was 120 to 130.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to absence of cerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are consistent with electrocerebral inactivity. Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is an 81-year-old male with fever and change of mental status.  No other clinical information available.
MEDICATIONS:  Cardizem, Reglan, vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a slow, mixed frequency pattern with theta and delta.  There are frontally predominant triphasic waves.  There are also some slow periodic complexes that appear in the right posterior quadrant more so than the left.  Stimulation of the patient produces a clear alerting response with a bit more fast theta frequency activity and a suggestion of a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  When the patient drifts off to sleep, the EEG becomes more significantly slow with more rhythmic slow mixed theta delta.
Heart rate irregular 72 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Marked background slowing.
Frontally predominant triphasic waves.
Occasional posteriorly predominant periodic complexes seen primarily on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Overall, this EEG is most suggestive of a toxic or metabolic pattern.  The triphasic waves improve with tactile stimulation and the patient shows a clear alerting with stimulation.  If seizures are an important consideration, additional EEG recording may be of value if this patient is thought to have seizures, particularly as  there is a right posterior periodic complex noted intermittently.
