The triphasic waves improve with tactile stimulation and the patient shows a clear alerting with stimulation.  If seizures are an important consideration, additional EEG recording may be of value if this patient is thought to have seizures, particularly as  there is a right posterior periodic complex noted intermittently.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 67-year-old woman with stroke and aphasia.  The patient has limited motor deficits, but significant aphasia.  The clinical team noted that the patient speaks occasionally but never on rounds.
MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, aspirin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not possible due to the patient's mental status, but photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates continuous focal slowing from the left hemisphere, some of which is sharply contoured with a phase reversal at T1.  There are T1 sharp waves noted intermittently.  The field of focal slowing is relatively diffuse throughout the left hemisphere, and there is disruption of the alpha rhythm.  In wakefulness, the right hemisphere demonstrates a well-formed alpha rhythm.
Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  Early stage I sleep was identified with limited vertex waves.  Of note, as the patient transitions to sleep, there is less in the way of rhythmic sharply contoured slowing.  Photic stimulation produces a driving response on the right but not the left.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to prominent, rhythmic slowing with sharp waves, really seen primarily in wakefulness on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no clear clinical correlates for the features described above.  There are brief transitions into stage II sleep for this individual, although sleep was not sustained, but the majority of the sharply contoured slowing and rhythmic slowing is seen in wakefulness.  Ongoing monitoring is essential.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 51-year-old male with history of severe headache, confusion and change in mental status as well as right intracerebral hemorrhage with internal jugular extension, hypertension, syncope, headache, diabetes.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best wakefulness reaches 6 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is no normal frontocentral beta.  Overall the patient is mainly recorded during sleep but during the limited wakefulness appears to be extensive theta.  No activating procedures were performed and clear staged changes were seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen at T4 intermittently at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen during wakefulness and at times with frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  72.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to a right mid temporal focal slowing as well as generalized slowing of frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right mid temporal region, which is consistent with a known hemorrhage.  In addition, there is evidence of moderate to diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status and responsiveness. Possible brain dead.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 56-year-old woman coded for 15 minutes on February 9, 2013.  Had hypothermia protocol on February 9, evaluated for electrocerebral silence.  Had no brain stem function and fentanyl was stopped at 2 a.m.  Temperature was 97.7.  Has a history of CHF, cardiomyopathy and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Coreg, lisinopril, Zocor, vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION:  Routine EEG was performed using the brain dead protocol with the standard 10-20 electrode placement system, with additional anterior temporal electrodes.  The patient was recorded while comatose and unresponsive.  No activating procedures were performed.
CLINICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There is cardiac and ventilator artifacts seen throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely abnormal background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture or frontal-central beta to the EEG.  At one point, the tech does ocular stimulation.  There appears to be no activity.  Overall, there is no clear electrocerebral activity; however, there is a vast amount of EKG and ventilator artifact throughout the recording.  Specifically, at Pz there is continuous, what appears to be an electrode pop or maybe a drip artifact.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to lack of normal cerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG does not reveal any clear electrocerebral activity.  However, due to the vast amount of artifact, no clear statement about electrocerebral silence can be made.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 49-year-old male with left frontal encephalomalacia and past history of epilepsy, found down this morning seizing with refractory status epilepticus and temperature of 101.3.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan 4 mg, Versed drip 160 mg, propofol,  succinylcholine,  etomidate, Dilantin 1500 mg.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient has been intubated and was somnolent.  Technical challenges for this EEG include problems with the electrical system utilized for the patient's hospital bed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow, low voltage, and relatively suppressed with slower, lower voltage delta, and scant amount of beta and alpha frequency activity.  Spontaneous arousals are associated with movement artifact.  The quantity of beta activity waxes and wanes in this record and in this low voltage record, shifting asymmetries were identified.
Stimulation of the patient as the recording continues clearly produces  an alerting response with eye opening and rolling eye movements are noted a little bit more prominently in later sections of the record.
Heart rate:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background including low voltage, slow delta pattern.
Scant, frontal central fast activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this patient with refractory status epilepticus, the current pattern is one of pharmacologic coma.  No epileptiform features were identified. Additional EEG recording was undertaken to make certain that no epileptiform features were overlooked.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 79-year-old male with past history of cryptococcal meningitis, pancytopenia, now with intermittent episodes of rigidity.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, multiple antibiotics, meropenem.  The patient received 16 mg of morphine and 2 mg of Ativan the day prior to the EEG.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was contractured in an unusual position and poorly responsive.  There was significant muscle artifact noted in the background.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the sections of the EEG without significant muscle, the background is diffusely slow with a mixture of rhythmic 2-4.5 Hz activity.  Stimulation of the patient does not activate the record, but does produce an increase in muscle artifact.  There is some variability of the record with some sections demonstrating a bit more slow featureless delta.
Heart rate:  162 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:  Marked background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a technically challenging record, but no focal or epileptiform features were noted.  Additional EEG recording was initiated in an attempt to capture one of these patient's motor behaviors.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 42-year-old woman with new-onset seizures on February 14, 2013 with tongue biting, jerking of the arms while they were stiffened and confused after the event as well as with a headache.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
HEART RATE:  60.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, stage I and stage II sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow wave seen intermittently at T3 as well as T4 at frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
There is a single sharp transient seen at T4 throughout the recording.
Seizures none.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral independent mid temporal focal slowing in addition to a sharp transient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral mid temporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  In addition, there is a single sharp transient in the right mid temporal region, its significance is unclear and it may reflect irritability in that region of the brain.  However, a prolonged recording capturing deeper stages of sleep for a longer period may help in clarifying the significance of this discharge.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 78-year-old woman with dementia, atrial fibrillation and GERD who presents with 3 days of right upper extremity shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while minimally responsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software along with the patient's events and notes were used to review the EEG.
Technical difficulties:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  Overall there is some intermittent spindle frequency bursts seen intermittently and some intermittent arterial vascular movements seen throughout the recording.  The patient was stimulated with suctioning.  There appears to be no variability or increased frequency in the EEG.
Heart rate:  72.
Abnormal discharges:  Generalized slow waves and decreased amplitude at 2-4 Hz seen throughout the recording.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing and diffuse oppression.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, however, the intermittent spindles suggest that it is at least in part due to medication effect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old male with history of anticoagulation status post fall with head trauma, right occipital, parietal and epidural hematoma, left parietal fracture, subdural hematoma, subarachnoid hemorrhage, post-traumatic seizure, status post 7 days prophylactic Keppra.  No additional seizures, numbness, weakness or tingling.
MEDICATIONS:  Tylenol, oxycodone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This was an awake and drowsy record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the EEG is reasonably well organized with a 10 Hertz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low-voltage, frontocentral beta.  There is scant theta in the frontocentral regions, right more so than the left.  There is a bit of shifting slowing and a bit more focal slowing on the right, as the patient becomes drowsy, but these are relatively subtle findings with a little underlying arrhythmic delta activity and some excess theta.  Vertex waves, K-complexes and spindles were noted in stage 2 sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
Subtle focal slowing from the right, particularly frontocentral region.
A little shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The focal features described in this EEG are dramatically improved compared to a previous study, February 26.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old gentleman, very limited historian, with epilepsy, blackout spells, mesial temporal sclerosis.  The patient states that he has been seizure-free for the past year.  He is illiterate and does not know his medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage, frontal central beta activity.  Although there is a great deal of eye movement artifact, in hyperventilation and relaxed wakefulness, there is very subtle underlying focal slowing in the right mid temporal region at T1, T2, T4.  Unfortunately, this is challenging to distinguish from the patient's nearly continuous eye blinks in wakefulness.  Features of drowsiness included an increase in theta beta which is relatively symmetric.  In drowsiness, there is some wicket as the patient transitions to stage I sleep with vertex waves and then spindles.
Photic stimulation elicited subtle driving.
Heart rate:  66 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very subtlety abnormal EEG due to Subtle focal slowing in the right temporal region noted in wakefulness and hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Because of the frequent eye blinks, to more completely evaluate this patient's focal features and potentially epileptiform features, a more prolonged study of capture sleep may be of value.  This is the patient's third EEG and is the first to capture focal features.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  78-year-old woman with dementia, atrial fibrillation, hospitalized on the 10th with right arm shaking and hallucinations.  Was found to have a markedly low voltage and suppressed EEGs.  Patient continues to have problematic behavior.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, vancomycin, Coumadin, Aricept, prednisone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This was a challenging EEG due to the patient's persistent movement.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a very low voltage and slow pattern.  The patient has constant mouth movements.  Despite this, there is some underlying, slow periodic sharply contoured delta from the left hemisphere and potentially some from the right.
Stimulation of the patient produces muscle artifact.  During some sections of the record the patient is awake and talking with a markedly slow background.
Although this is a challenging EEG, there is a suggesting of additional asymmetry with a bit more rhythmic theta from the left hemisphere compared to the right.
Heart rate irregular, 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Very challenging awake EEG but abnormal due to:
Marked background slowing.
A suggesting of an asymmetry with a bit more arrhythmic theta from the left compared to the right.
Questionable slow periodic delta from the left and potentially from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  To more completely evaluate this patient, a sleep EEG would be helpful.  This would eliminate the muscle artifact noted in wakefulness.  A single, more prolonged bedside recording, with sleep would eliminate the muscle and chew artifacts.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 28-year-old woman, admitted to the hospital on 13th after an episode, where she had a loss of consciousness, fell, and hit her face followed by a generalized tonic-clonic seizure.  One prior similar episode, normal CT.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is in awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm.  Central mu-activity was noted, the mu-activity was 9 Hz, but testing was not performed to confirm this.
Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements, anterior spread of the alpha rhythm, and increase in beta followed by theta with rare vertex waves.  The patient was transitioned into stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles during photic stimulation.  Despite this, a driving response was elicited.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in theta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep due to
Slight slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  The mild slowing of the alpha rhythm is a nonspecific finding.  It may be a part of postictal state or other diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a followup study may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman with a history of dementia, schizophrenia, head trauma, and recent breakthrough seizures
.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, Celexa.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Previously EEG's were not available for comparison.  Photic stimulation was completed, but hyperventilation was not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is awake.  She had significant oral dyskinesia and there is muscle activity that persists even if she becomes drowsy.  In the waking recording, there is primarily a theta frequency pattern.  As she transitions into stage I sleep, vertex waves were seen.  There is a subtle, discrete, underlying low amplitude spike in the left frontocentral region which can be differentiated from artifact.  There may be one as well on the right (region not as well defined) and on one occasion the spike is followed by a vertex wave.  Bursts of arrhythmic, frontally predominant delta are noted as the patient transitions to deeper stages of sleep.  There is also some Firda in that transition to sleep.
Photic stimulation produces a great deal of muscle and photoelectric artifact, right greater than left, but there is driving at 15 Hz.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to:
Significant background slowing.
Disorganization.
Discrete, low voltage frontocentral sharps.
There was a previous EEG from 08/28/2012 demonstrating frequent left hemispheric maximal anterior slowing.  This EEG is essentially congruent with that pattern; although, today's EEG is significantly slower.  The low voltage spikes are also ipsilateral to the left.  In that this EEG today is significantly slower than the previous study, correlation with clinical history is important as medications, metabolic disorders, or progression of her dementia may all contribute to the pattern identified above.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 38-year-old gentleman with left craniectomy due to gunshot.  He returned from operating room this morning with seizure activity, treated with Ativan.  There is no T1 and T2 electrodes due to skull defect.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, midazolam, morphine, Ativan, Keppra, and Zofran.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  There is no T1 and T2 electrodes due to his skull defect.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In the sedated state, there is diffuse slowing of the background consisting of delta activity, 2-3 Hz frequency, most pronounced on the left side.  There is intermittent alpha activity with a frequency of 8-9 Hz, lasting for 1-2 seconds, most pronounced in frontotemporal region.  There is hemispheric asymmetry characterized by higher amplitude in left hemispheric regions, most pronounced in the frontotemporal areas.  There is slowing of the background activity in delta range with a frequency of 2-3 Hz almost continuously.  There is spontaneous variability seen with increase in background frequency.  There is also reactivity to stimulation.  There is no epileptiform activity or clinical seizures noted during this recording.  Heart rate was 100 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background activity in delta and theta range intermixed with intermittent alpha activity.
Focal slowing and breach in left cerebral hemisphere, most pronounced in frontotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of metabolic, toxic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy or due to the effect of sedating medications.  Left focal slowing is indicative of focal structural dysfunction in the left cerebral hemisphere, most pronounced in frontotemporal region.  Breach rhythm is consistent with a history of left craniectomy.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or of intermittent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 63-year-old man with a past history of a motor vehicle accident in 1970 with a subsequent coma.  The patient developed post traumatic epilepsy and has had recent seizures.  His highest seizure frequency has been as high as 10 seizures per day.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed on this patient using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG monitoring.  During the course of the recording hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The recording captures wakefulness through stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.
Recording was 22minutes in duration.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the record opens there is a symmetric 8.5 to 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm that is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontocentral beta activity that is present as well.  Drowsiness is characterized by a decrease in eye blinks and the appearance of slowing in the theta range in the occipital electrodes.  There is the appearance of slow rolling eye movements.  Throughout the recording there is intermittent focal slowing noted over the right hemisphere.  This is most prominent over the right frontotemporal region, but also extends into the frontocentral regions.  On several occasions throughout the recording there are medium amplitude sharp waves identified that are maximal in the right frontal region phase reversing at F8 and T4.  These occur as isolated sharp waves.  Hyperventilation induces generalized slowing in the tracing.  Photic stimulation does not induce a significant photic driving response.  There were no clinical events recorded or noted by the technician during the recording epoch.  There were no electrographic seizures identified. Heart rate varied from 60-80.
IMPRESSION:  In summary, this is an abnormal EEG capturing wakefulness through stage 2 sleep due to the presence of focal slowing over the right hemisphere and rare sharp waves noted over the right frontotemporal region.  The appearance of focal slowing may be suggestive of a structural brain lesion in this region.  Sharp waves have epileptiform potential.

STUDY DURATION:  6 hours.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure classification.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old woman with history of MS, seizures, GERD, anemia, kidney stones, described as episodes of eyes rolling up, spit coming out of the mouth, and tonic clonic shaking for about 20 minutes, also leg spasms.  She is here for seizure classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, baclofen, levothyroxine, nitrofurantoin, Percocet, Oxycontin, Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  A long term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded mainly in wakefulness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement and A2 electrode artifact seen during this recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontal central beta.
Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness mainly during the 6 hours.
Abnormal discharges:  Frequent focal slowing seen at T3, at times at F7/T3 at a frequency at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left mid temporal and anterior temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left mid to anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 60-year-old male with a history of polysubstance abuse who was admitted for narcotic withdrawal and encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS:
RECORDING TIMES:  The record starts at 10:29 a.m. It ends at 10:53 a.m.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a bedside EEG recording.  As the record opens, there is a low voltage 10 to 11 Hz posterior dominant rhythm that is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  There is a small to moderate amount of central theta activity that persists throughout the recording and is suggestive of background slowing.  Throughout the recording, there is a repetitive rhythmic eye blink eye movement abnormality noted in __________ that obscures much of the recording in that region.
At 10:43 a.m., the patient was noticed clinically to become agitated but there was no associated change in the background cerebral activity.
Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and did not induce a significant photic driving response.  There were no spikes or sharp waves identified.  There were no electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to the presence of diffuse bihemispheric mild slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Bihemispheric slowing may be seen in toxic metabolic encephalopathies or in diffuse underlying structural brain injury.  A single episode of agitation was not associated with any change in the background cerebellar EEG.

DURATION OF STUDY:  Study date 03/26/2013 through 03/27/2013, for a total of 15 hours.  However, due to technical difficulties only 5 hours could be reviewed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  39-year-old woman with episode of bilateral arm stiffness and gaze deviated to the right.  Has 4-5 seizures in the past month, screaming, with a history of Lennox-Gastaut, mental retardation.  Follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan, famotidine, Lovenox, topiramate, Flagyl, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software in addition to nurse's notes were used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and frontocentral beta.  Overall, there are theta delta mixed frequencies intermingled with multiple multifocal spikes which I will describe in Abnormal Discharges.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Multifocal spikes seen at O1, O2, T6, Fp1, Fp2, T3, and P4.  However, the spikes are mainly seen at O1 and O2 and Fp1/Fp2.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  During the record, there are multiple seizures which in the EEG appear to begin suddenly and display rhythmic, sharply contoured theta intermixed with beta that at times appears to be maximal frontally and then centrally with an overlying rhythmic occipital sharp focus.  The maximal focus or origin of the seizure is unclear.  It is also atypical as it does not appear to evolve as it suddenly starts, remains in the EEG at almost this irregular but continuous frequency, and then appears to slowly dissipate.  During these discharges, the patient appears to move her head side to side and sometimes moves her arms in a wild fashion.  On 1 occasion, her mouth appeared to twitch in the video.  The duration of these episodes can be anywhere from 1 or 2 minutes to prolonged 38-minute seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to multiple seizures with unclear origin and multifocal spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multiple generalized seizures with unclear origin as well as multiple areas of irritability and structural dysfunction as well as diffuse dysfunction consistent with diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy.
These findings were communicated to the primary team as soon as the EEG was read.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old woman admitted on the 7th with multiple seizures.  Previous EEG is not available for comparison.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is awake.  The background is diffusely slow with a mixture of theta and smaller amounts of delta.  Occasional, right or left anterior temporal spikes were noted in the background.  There are independent, right or left temporal sharp waves and spikes noted in wakefulness.  There are more noted on the right in comparison to the left.  In addition, the epileptiform activity is at times complex with an extensive field of spread or some variability in terms of maximum at T2 and/or spread to the frontal regions.  As the patient became a bit drowsy, epileptiform activity with the field of spread which included posterotemporal regions and even a polyspike component was noted.  During photic stimulation, there are independent sharp waves or spikes noted.  In addition, during the 3 Hz stimulation, there is a run of rhythmic 4 Hz activity, but without frequency evolution.  Similar activity was not seen on the left.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Complex epileptiform activity with independent sharp waves or spikes noted from either hemisphere typically with a temporal maximum, T1 or T2, but sometimes with a polyspike component or spread to the frontal regions or occipital regions.
An unusual discharge during the 3 Hz stimulation which may have represented a subclinical seizure.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  The epileptiform activity is more complex than is typically seen in garden variety temporal lobe epilepsy.  There is a polyspike component and a generous field of spread.  In this particular EEG, there is more epileptiform activity on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 30-year-old gentleman status post cranioplasty, who presents with shaking and suspected seizures.  He has a history of TBI on 10/26/2012.  His last seizure was on 03/21/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with additional single-lead EKG electrode.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9-10 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  There are almost continuous left temporal slowing at F7/T3 during wakefulness and sleep, consisting of 2-3 Hz delta frequency.  There are also focal slow waves seen independently in the bilateral frontal regions almost continuously throughout the recording at 3-4 Hz.  Hyperventilation results in accentuation of slowing, most pronounced on the left side.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and resulted in a driving response.  Heart rate was 70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to bifrontal slowing and left temporal slowing.  No epileptiform activities or seizures are identified in this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of focal structural cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral frontal regions and left temporal regions, which is consistent with a known history of TBI.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen or captured.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 9, last seizure was 1 week ago.  The patient reports seizures during sleep with tongue biting, increasingly frequent, 6 to 8 within the last 6 months.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient seems to be drowsy throughout much of the EEG, but in wakefulness there is excess beta and excess theta in a somewhat poorly organized record.  In the sharply contoured background, there is prominent frontal beta and as the patient becomes drowsy there is some paroxysmal high amplitude bursts, but no definitive frontal sharp waves or spikes.
Hyperventilation seems to accentuate the background slowing and there is a very subtle focality with perhaps a bit more left-sided focal slowing in hyperventilation compared to the right.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for generous beta, but a driving response.  Heart rate is 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG in wakefulness and sleep due to:
Somewhat disorganized pattern for age.
Excess beta.
Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The excess beta could be due to medication effect or anxiety.  The excess theta suggests a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function.  It is important to have a complete list of this patient's medications.  No definitive sharp waves or spikes were seen.  A more prolonged study capturing sleep may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 45-year-old man who presents with multiple seizures on the day before the recording characterized by loss of consciousness, left-sided shaky and left gaze deviation.  The patient has a history of a left frontal hemorrhage resulting in aphasia.  The patient is noncompliant with medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, aspirin, lisinopril.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one channel EKG.  Wakefulness and sleep were captured.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a bilateral alpha rhythm which is about 9.5 Hz on the left hemisphere, but it is disrupted on the right hemisphere.  There is bifrontal slowing more pronounced on the right hemisphere.  The slowing is frequently sharply contoured.  Sleep was characterized by vertex waves and K complexes.  The right focal slowing was more pronounced during sleep.
There were discreet sharps on the right hemisphere in the FP2 region and rarely in T2 region.
Hyperventilation was performed which showed diffuse slowing of the record with increase in amplitude.
Photic stimulation was performed which did not show any changes in the EEG record.
Heart rate 84 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Bifrontal slowing.
Right focal slowing with disrupted alpha on the right side.  The slowing was frequently sharply contoured.
FP2 and T2 sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is suggestive of an underlying structural abnormality in the right hemisphere causing focal slowing which is sharply contoured on that side.  The sharps are indicative of the underlying epileptogenicity in this region.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 58-year-old female with episodes of seizure-like activity.  When she tried to get up, had shaking of left arms followed by shaking of her right upper and lower extremities for a minute.  This was followed by post event confusion for 5 minutes.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Significant for diabetes, hypertension, and cervical stenosis.
MEDICATIONS:  Includes Keppra, Motrin, and insulin.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with addition of T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 9-10 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuated with eye opening.  There was presence of low-amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which was distributed symmetrically.  There were occasional bursts of focal slowing in the left anterior and mid temporal region consisting of 2.5-3 Hz delta frequency lasting for 1-2 seconds.  Drowsiness was characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  No epileptiform activity or seizures captured in this study.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to occasional bursts of focal slowing in the left anterior and mid temporal regions during wakefulness and drowsiness.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Focal slowing in the left hemisphere suggestive of a structural abnormality in the left hemisphere or left temporal dysfunction.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were seen in this recording.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or of intermittent seizures.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat sleep-deprived EEG or a 24-hour video EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 70-year-old found unresponsive in her kitchen, suffered a generalized tonic-clonic seizure of 30 seconds' duration en route to hospital.  Eyes deviated to the right.  Past left MCA infarct.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Versed, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a pattern with diffuse beta and bursts of spindles.  In addition, there is arrhythmic delta activity and the beta drops out for a burst of arrhythmic delta activity.  The arrhythmic delta activity is somewhat more remarkable on the right, and there is subtle underlying sharply contoured slowing in the right posterior occipital region as well as a bit more attenuation of faster frequency activity on the right relative to the left.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in rhythmic theta.  As the recording continues, the background EEG is richer in both beta and theta.  The initial asymmetry is a bit less prominent.
Heart rate 72 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a dynamic but abnormal EEG due to:
Initial markedly slow pattern with intermittent paroxysmal beta.
At the end of the record, the EEG remains quite slow, but there is an increase in beta and a decrease in the arrhythmic delta activity.
An asymmetry with a bit more arrhythmic delta activity in the right posterior quadrant.
Some sharply contoured slowing in the right posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The postictal state and the use of sedative hypnotic medications may play a role in the marked background slowing and the beta in this record.  No seizures were recorded.  The arrhythmic delta activity may be correlated with imaging.  If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing is suggested, given the sharply contoured slowing described above.

REASON FOR THE STUDY:  Declining memory.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 76-year-old man with declining memory, talks to himself.  The patient also reports dizzy spells about 2-3 times per week.  Last episode was 8 months ago with fall and loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Klonopin, Glucophage, Pravachol.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Diabetes and hypertension.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one channel of EKG.  Wakefulness was recorded during the EEG.  Activating procedures include hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS:  There was continuous eye movement artifact in the first half of the recording, which impedes correct evaluation of the cerebral activity in the frontal leads.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz frequency, 30-50 microvolts in amplitude, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  There is excess theta noted in the frontal leads in the section without the eye movement artifact.
Sleep was not achieved during the recording.
Hyperventilation was performed, which did not bring about significant change in the recording.
Photic stimulation did not elicit any changes in the record.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Occasional T3 focal slow waves at 2-4 Hz in frequency and 50-70 microvolts in amplitude.
Mildly excess theta in the frontal leads.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Left mid temporal intermittent slowing.
Mildly excess theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is suggestive of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left mid temporal region which is non-specific with regards to etiology.  The excess theta in the frontal leads may indicate drowsiness or a mild diffuse encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old left-handed woman admitted February 2013 with new onset seizures and a cystic brain mass status post day #1 after resection of right parietal tumor.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Morphine, Zofran, and Percocet.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was noted to have a prominent right craniotomy.
TECHNICAL:  There is some muscle artifact, but overall this is a technically satisfactory record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the EEG is remarkable for a mixture of arrhythmic mixed theta-delta from the right hemisphere.  The left hemisphere has more of a medium amplitude more rhythmic theta pattern.  Although the patient is awake and following commands, an alpha rhythm was not identified.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, more of a rhythmic theta pattern is noted on the left with a mixture of arrhythmic delta and theta on the right.  Asymmetric spindles were noted out of the right central region.  In the context of a breech rhythm, there is some very subtle right frontocentral sharp waves noted.
The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with spindle activity.
Heart rate 50 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Continuous focal slowing on the right.
Background slowing on the left.
Rare discrete right frontal sharp waves.
FIRDA noted at the close of the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural process on the right.  There are some subtle sharp waves noted in the region of the craniotomy on the right.  The bilateral background slowing suggests a bihemispheric process and may be part of this patient's postoperative pattern.  Correlation with imaging and clinical history is suggested.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Twenty-two minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 19-year-old woman with a history of seizures since the age of 2, now presents with concern for status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include:  Lamictal and 8 mg of Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of diffuse rhythmic and semi-rhythmic high amplitude frontally predominant delta activity mixed with bursts of diffuse spindle-like wave forms.  No normal sleep architecture is captured.  At least 3 electrographic seizures are noted. These seizures start with approximately a 10-12 second run of fast activity most pronounced over the right occipital lead.  This activity eventually spread to the right anterior region. During this spread, rhythmic more frequency theta and delta activity are captured over the right anterior leads with some reflection over the left hemisphere.  Seizure offset is gradual.  Total seizure duration is approximately one minute.  Increase in heart rate up to 150 to 180 beats a minutes is noted during seizure.  During one of the seizures, the patient bites on the ET tube.
A single EKG lead demonstrates continued tachycardia with heart rate on average of approximately 120 beats a minute.
FINDINGS:
At least 3 electrographic seizures with right occipital onset lasting approximately 1 minute.
Runs of bilateral posterior fast activity.
Moderate to severe diffuse slowing.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalogram due to moderate diffuse slowing, intermittent high frequency activity observed posteriorly, as well as 3 focal right hemisphere electrographic seizures with onset of right occipital leads.  Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific cerebral dysfunction, that in this case could partially be related to medications.  There is a seizure onset focus that is suspected to be over the right occipital region.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team.

DATE OF THE RECORDING:  05/16/2013 from approximately 2:00 p.m. until 05/17/2013 until approximately 2:00 p.m.  Total time of the recording is approximately 24 hours.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 19-year-old woman with a history of seizures who now presents with recurrent complex partial seizures and a change in behavior, subsequently found to have status epilepticus.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Versed, phenobarbital.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
The recording was reviewed on several occasions during the 24 hour recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency gradient.  The background consists mostly of a mixture of low amplitude delta activity with underwriting faster frequencies and 1 to 4 second diffuse bursts of spindle-like waveforms.  No clear normal architecture is captured.  Multiple electrographic seizures of variable duration are noted throughout the recording.  Seizure duration varies from 30 seconds to over 30 minutes.  Seizure onset is often poorly localized.  Some start with bilateral central frontal fast activity that increases in amplitude and decreases in frequency to the alpha range.  More prolonged seizures start with diffuse frontally predominant delta activity with underwriting by frontocentral faster activity.  This activity increases in amplitude and decreases in frequency, and spreads throughout other cerebral regions.  During multiple long seizures the seizure output is not clear.  There has been some tachycardia noted on a electrocardiogram lead.  During seizures heart rate increases to approximately 120 beats per minute.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent electrographic seizures with poor localization and lateralization with variable durations from 30 seconds to approximately 30 minutes.
Moderate to severe diffuse slowing and low amplitude attenuation.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 24 hour EEG due to intermittent seizures and frank status epilepticus as well as moderate to severe diffuse slowing.  The slowing indicates etiological nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction, and in this case likely related to medication effect.  These findings were conveyed to the Primary Team.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 70-year-old woman with a history of left MCA stroke who presents with a generalized tonic-clonic convulsion that started with eyes deviation to the right.  The event occurred approximately 14 days ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications:  Keppra, clonidine, Plavix, amlodipine.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording is performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Step photic stimulation was performed.  The recording was performed in the laboratory.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is right-to-left interhemispheric asymmetry with faster waveforms at higher amplitudes over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right consists of moderate amplitude well-formed and modulated 10Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient over the right as well.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left reaches approximately 9 to 9.5 Hz alpha activity.  There is an AP gradient over the left hemisphere with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Additional polymorphic theta activity is present over the left hemisphere, most pronounced over the left temporal region.  During drowsiness the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates and bursts of theta are captured.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.  A regular cardiac rhythm is noted on the single EKG lead.  There is diffuse excess beta throughout the recording.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Continuous mild left hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the left temporal region.
Excess beta.
No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 21-minute EEG due to mild continuous left hemispheric slowing, most pronounced over the left temporal region.  This findings indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and in this patient is consistent with a history of left middle cerebral artery territory stroke.  Excess beta could be secondary to the medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persists a repeat study with stage II sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 52-year-old woman with a 10-year history of epilepsy, last seizure 2 days ago with shaking, eye rolling, foaming at the mouth, incontinence of bowel and bladder.
PAST HISTORY:  MI and stroke with right hemiparesis, weakness, depression, and bipolar disease.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Depakote, Klonopin, and albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was completed.  Photic stimulation was deferred.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
TECHNICAL:  There is a fair amount of muscle artifact noted in the background.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is somewhat disorganized.  There is a glimpse of an 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a bit more variability in the alpha rhythm than would otherwise be expected.  There is excess background theta.  As the patient becomes a bit drowsy, there is occasional focal slowing characterized by subtle underlying theta or delta from the left hemisphere.  Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.
Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 108 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Background disorganization.
Subtle underlying slowing in the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in this awake and briefly drowsy record.  If additional information is needed, a repeat tracing capturing sleep may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 25-year-old male with recurrent ganglioglioma resections in childhood, patient states that he has been seizure free since 2007.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  A prominent craniotomy defect was noted in the left temporal and central regions.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a well formed, __________ rhythm reaching 70 microvolts in amplitude.  A prominent breech rhythm was noted with accentuation of beta activity in the left temporal and central regions almost involving the right central region.  Intermittent underlying focal slowing was noted in the left central temporal region and was clearly accentuated by hyperventilation.  In addition, there was some shifting and slowing also accentuated by hyperventilation.  In this sharply contoured record, as the patient transitions in and out of stage I and stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles, there are a handful of sharp waves noted in the left central temporal region with an after going slow wave.  Other features of the drowsy record include an accentuation of the focal slowing in the left hemisphere including frontocentral and posterior temporal regions with attenuation of activity in drowsiness in the left frontocentral region.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off into stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate:  60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Left hemispheric focal slowing with variable maxima depending on whether the patient is awake, asleep or performing hyperventilation.
In the context of a breech rhythm and a sharply contoured record, there are a handful of sharp waves with after going slow waves in the left mid temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings described above are congruent with a structural process on the left as well as a breech rhythm.  A breech rhythm can accentuate background activity but there are a handful of sharp waves with after going slow waves suggesting an ongoing potential for seizures in this seizure free adult.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 44-year-old man with history of seizures, attempted suicide, found at the bottom of the stairs with a sheet around his neck confused, found to have hydrocephalus, subdural, subarachnoid, and an EVD placed, has eye twitching and right sided gaze deviation with anxiety, depression, pancreatitis and schizophrenia/bipolar.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lamictal, phenobarbital, paroxetine, trazodone, Prilosec, Percocet as needed, hydroxyzine, meloxicam, vancomycin, Zofran, Zosyn, Ativan and Versed as needed.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during lethargy.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to an absent posterior dominant rhythm without any normal frontocentral beta.  Overall, the background is disorganized and has data slowing seen continuously throughout it.  In addition, there is continuous frontal eye movements throughout the recording.
Activating procedures were not performed and no normal sleep architecture was seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz and amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen continuously.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  102.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 44-year-old man who was admitted to Temple after an attempted suicide.  He was found down the stairs with sheets around his neck 2 weeks ago.  He has a ventriculostomy in place.
MEDICATIONS:  Morphine, Lamictal and phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated and in a hard collar.  Impedances were acceptable.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This bedside portable IC record demonstrates an awake individual with generous movement artifact and diffusely slow pattern with a 5-6 Hz alpha rhythm.  There are occasional simple sharp waves seen in right frontal or mid temporal regions.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the EEG becomes low voltage and much more featureless.
Heart rate was 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
Prominent attenuation in drowsiness.
A handful of simple sharp waves noted on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The diffuse background slowing supports a bihemispheric process.  The simple sharp waves noted on the right may be confounded by the ventric.  No seizures were recorded and previous EEGs were not available at this time.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  21 minutes
CONDITION OF RECORDING:  The recording is performed using standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.
HISTORY:  The patient is a 45-year-old woman with a past medical history of seizures.  Her last seizure occurred two to three weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra and Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a low __________ modulated 10.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  __________ posterior frequency with subsequent frequency of low amplitude anteriorly.  During sleep, symmetrical vertex waves and sleep spindles are captured.  Intermittent left temporal theta delta activity is observed.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent moderate left temporal slowing.
Epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 21-minute EEG due to intermittent left temporal moderate slowing.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy .

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  21 minutes, 35 seconds.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 45-year-old man who presents with right frontal intracranial hemorrhage and generalized tonic-clonic convulsion.  Past medical history is also notable for a stroke.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and Keppra; 2 mg of Ativan given in the emergency room.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of polymorphic 9 Hz alpha activity that is unstable.  The anterior to posterior frequency gradient is weak.  Diffuse beta is observed.  Additional polymorphic diffuse theta and delta activity, as well as frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA) are captured.  No normal sleep architecture is observed; however, periods of quiescence are noted.  There is paucity of faster frequencies over the right hemisphere, notably over the right lateral leads.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
FINDINGS:
Mild to moderate diffuse slowing.
FIRDA.
Paucity of faster frequencies over the right hemisphere, especially over the right temporal region.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 21-minute EEG due to mild to moderate diffuse slowing and right hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the right temporal region.  Diffuse slowing indicates neurologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal cerebral slowing is suggestive of underlying focal cerebral dysfunction.  Excess beta is secondary to medication effect such as barbiturates or benzodiazepines.  FIRDA could be seen in various encephalopathies, increased intracranial pressure, or deep white matter lesions.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does no preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 64-year-old man with history of a motor vehicle accident in 1970 that left him in a coma for 6 months, who presents with onset of seizures for 2 years with recent seizures, 10 seizures in a day 2 weeks ago.  Follow-up EEG has had 2 seizures, one in May and the last one in June, both with loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:  Amlodipine, carbamazepine.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterotemporal and a single-lead EKG electrode.
The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Stage 1.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen almost frequently at F4/F8 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 millivolts.
At times there is frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  96.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right frontal slowing in addition to frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right frontal region which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  The FIRDA noticed during the EEG may signify a bilateral white matter frontal lesion or can be seen with increased intracranial hypertension but is usually nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.  This EEG is similar to the one described read on March 22, 2013.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 80-year-old man admitted for right lung lobectomy due to cancer, found to have decreased oxygen saturation and witnessed seizure, with a past medical history of colon cancer, seizures, hepatitis C, psoriasis, dementia, lung cancer, colon surgery, and prior EEG in July 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, albuterol, famotidine, cefepime, morphine, heparin, clonazepam, lisinopril, Aricept, and Zofran.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontal central beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recording during wakefulness and drowsiness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen intermittently at T3 and independently at T4 and sometimes at F4/C4 and sometimes at F3/C3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
There is excessive theta at 5-7 Hz in wakefulness.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  72.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to mild generalized slowing as well as focal slowing in the bilateral mid temporal region as well as central frontal regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral mid temporal regions, as well as frontal central regions, in addition to mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, all of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No clear seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Prolonged convulsive status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  85-year-old woman with a history of left MCA stroke and t-PA in August of 2012, hypertension, hypothyroidism that presents with prolonged convulsive status.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Continuous muscle artifact throughout the temporalis and central region of the head.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is an absence of normal brain activity and there is an overlying muscle artifact throughout the recording.  There appears to be no variability or reactivity to the EEG and overall there is a low amplitude slowing seen throughout the recording.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slowing at 1-3 Hz and an amplitude of less than 10 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  114, irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to marked to severe generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of marked generalized cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Prolonged convulsive status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  85-year-old woman with a history of left MCA stroke and t-PA in August of 2012, hypertension, hypothyroidism that presents with prolonged convulsive status.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Continuous muscle artifact throughout the temporalis and central region of the head.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is an absence of normal brain activity and there is an overlying muscle artifact throughout the recording.  There appears to be no variability or reactivity to the EEG and overall there is a low amplitude slowing seen throughout the recording.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slowing at 1-3 Hz and an amplitude of less than 10 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  114, irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to marked to severe generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of marked generalized cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 46-year-old man with history of recurrent intracranial hemorrhage, episodes of unclear etiology who now presents with new left temporal hemorrhage and multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications Keppra, loaded with Dilantin, phenobarbital, and placed on Versed drip later in the recording.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording is performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1-T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  CT compatible electrodes were used.  The recording was reviewed intermittently throughout the 24 hour period by an  attending neurologist.  Medical staff notes and nursing staff notes were reviewed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is right-to-left interhemispheric asymmetry with lower waveforms and high amplitudes over the left hemisphere.  The background over the right hemisphere has a posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 8-9 Hz activity with weak anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  There is additional polymorphic theta activity observed over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of approximately 8 Hz theta activity without clear anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background over the left hemisphere consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity.  Throughout the recording additional diffuse low amplitude rhythmic slow delta activity is captured.  As the recording progresses, frequency of this delta activity becomes more pronounced.  Additionally as the recording progresses the patient appears to start having poorly formed electrographic seizures emanating from the left temporal parietal region.  These seizures are characterized by rhythmic theta activity most pronounced over the left lateral leads.  As the recording progresses seizures appear to spread diffusely and are characterized by diffuse rhythmic delta activity, with associated blink artifact.  Clinically the patient appears to have a rhythmic bilateral eye blinking.  Ativan was administered but did not result in cessation of status epilepticus.  The patient was subsequently loaded with IV Dilantin.  This resulted in resolution of generalized status epilepticus; however, he continued to have focal left temporal parietal status epilepticus.  The patient was subsequently intubated at 11:52 p.m. using propofol.  This resulted in abrupt discontinuation of status epilepticus as well as diffuse burst suppression.  That lasted several minutes.  As burst suppression decreased discrete moderate amplitude sharp waves were observed over the left temporoparietal region.  Their frequency gradually increased to approximately 1 Hz.  These discharges constituted PLEDs.  These discharges are accompanied by lower amplitude fast activity thus representing PLEDs-plus.  Occasionally frequency of these discharges increases but never lasts longer than 10 seconds.  This constitutes a brief ictal rhythmic discharges (BIRDS).
FINDINGS:  Left temporal parietal seizures that slowly evolved into generalized status epilepticus.  PLEDs and PLEDs-plus emanating from the left temporal parietal region observed after 12 a.m..  Diffuse background slowing and discontinuation.  Focal left hemispheric slowing.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 24-hour continuous audio video electroencephalogram  monitoring due to gradual resolution of focal left temporal parietal status epilepticus that evolves into generalized status epilepticus.  __________ status epilepticus resolves with administration of Ativan and Dilantin.  However, focal left temporal parietal status epilepticus persists.  It resolves with administration of anesthetic  agent and initiation of phenobarbital.  However, periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges are still observed at that time.  Diffuse background slowing indicates __________ nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal left hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural etiology and in this patient is partially related to postictal phenomenon.  These findings were conveyed to the Neurology primary team.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old man with history of right MCA stroke and localization-related epilepsy, who presents with seizures.  He also has a history of drug and ethanol abuse.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captures the patient in a vague and lethargic state.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5-9 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening, well formed on the left side.  There is moderate amount of frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness and stage 2 sleep are characterized by slowing of the background, slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifacts, and presence of posts and vertex sharp waves.  Continuous focal slowing of continuous focal slow waves seen at F8/T4 at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 30-60 microvolts.  Sharp waves are seen with shifting negativity at FP1/FP2/F4, which occur frequently during the recording.  There are periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges seen in the right hemisphere, maximum at right superior frontal and anterior temporal region occurring with a frequency of 0.5-1.5 Hz with no evolution.  There are excess of 7-7.5 Hz theta activity seen during short period of wakefulness.  Heart rate was 70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing the patient at brief period of wakefulness and lethargic state due to:  One, diffuse slowing of the background.  Two, presence of sharp waves in FP1/FP2, and F8 and right periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges.  Three, almost continuous focal slowing of right temporal region.  There was no electrographic seizures during this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the prefrontal region.  In addition, there is evidence of continued structural focal cerebral dysfunction in the right anterior temporal region, which has a high correlation with the lesion in that region consistent with patient's history of right middle cerebral artery stroke.  No electrographic seizures were seen.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 45-year-old woman, admitted to the ICU after multiple repetitive convulsions, followed by agitation.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed 6 mg, Neurontin, Keppra, Topamax, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated and obtunded.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a continuous pattern, which ranges from a more sedated sleep pattern, with some features of stage II sleep including spindle and vertex waves.  Intermittent arousal is associated with a 7 Hz background.  In this bedside, ICU record, there are minor artifacts in the posterior regions and some shifting slowing.
Heart rate 120 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a slow pattern.
Minor shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.  No epileptiform features were identified.  Some of the shifting slowing described above may include head rocking artifact for this bedside portable record.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 74-year-old woman with seizures following a medical illness and missing her gabapentin.  Currently event free, but with numbness and tremor in the left arm.  Keppra taper in progress.
MEDICATIONS:  Gabapentin, Keppra, Synthroid and many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is a routine EEG with satisfactory impedances aside from the T1-T2 electrode.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm, which is somewhat disrupted on the right compared to the left.  There are bursts of bilateral, relatively rhythmic slowing.  In addition, there is shifting slowing, more so on the right compared to the left.  Features of drowsiness include a decrease in muscle.  In addition, focal slowing from the right becomes a bit more prominent as the patient transitions in and out of drowsiness.  The focal slowing on the right is intermittent.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was relatively drowsy and did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to.
Focal slowing from the right hemisphere with disruption of faster frequency activity and intermittent disruption of the alpha rhythm.
Shifting slowing.
Occasional bursts of bilateral slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the fourth EEG for this individual.  No epileptiform features have been seen in this EEG or the two previous EEGs.  The focal slowing on the right is ipsilateral to the
patient's stroke.  Of note, the last two EEGs have shown a bit more in the way of generalized features including generalized slowing or shifting slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 64-year-old male status post MVA many years ago with prolonged coma.  The patient had epilepsy in recent years.  Recently hospitalized for multiple repetitive seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  No clinical or electrographic seizures were noted in this section of the record, which includes wakefulness and sleep.  The patient was noted to have intermittent twitching of the right shoulder.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  Wakefulness and sleep:  In wakefulness and sleep, the background EEG includes a well-organized background with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  As the patient becomes drowsy, subtle focal slowing was noted in the right hemisphere.  This is characterized by an initial drop out of faster frequency activity on the right with a bit more slow and slightly more irregular delta.  Other features of sleep include bursts of background slowing.  There is some muscle twitch artifact noted as the patient drifts off into sleep.  Although clinically the patient has unilateral shoulder jerking, the twitch artifact is bilateral on some occasions, and on other occasions very low voltage in sleep in the right scalp electrodes.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Very subtly abnormal EEG in wakefulness and sleep due to:  Subtle focal slowing in the right hemisphere noted primarily in sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive epileptiform features were noted.  Some muscle twitch artifact was picked up.  Additional EEG recording will be obtained in an attempt to characterize this patient's seizures.
